column6: PUMA Speed Light up V Kids Sneaker (Toddler/Little Kid/Big Kid)
column14: I purchased two pairs of the grey/white/orange/red sneaker in size 11 for my 4 and 5 year old boys. I usually do not care for the look of Velcro shoes, but needed something my boys would be able to put on themselves. These are ADORABLE!!!! I loooove how they look sleek and not clunky like a lot of sneakers. Based on some reviews and by scouring the web for Pumas shoe measurement chart, I bought a size up and they fit perfectly. If it is helpful, my boys feet were between 16.5 and 17 cm when measured...very professionally by tracing their feet on paper and using my trusty wooden ruler! My onlyyyy reservation about these shoes is that the first thing my husband said when he saw the kids wearing them is "what's with the pink lights?" The outside red stripe lights up and well...honestly it does kind of look pink when it lights up, but my boys haven't noticed. They love them, but I am slightly nervous about sending my 5 year old to kindergarten in them because of the pinkish looking lights. We'll see - if it causes a problem, I plan to wash them in the washing machine a few times to kill the lights and can hopefully continue to enjoy these super cute shoes!!

column13: This is the one!  Holds a larger cell phone too!
column14:
I ordered several different bags from Amazon for a wedding and this was the clear winner. It's well made - there are no sharp edges on the metal and even thought the strap is a chain, it's soft - no sharpness to it at all. The clasp on top has a few fake diamonds but it's tasteful. Just enough to give it a tiny bit of sparkle without being too "out there" or blingy.

Now, let's talk about the size. If you have one of the newer larger cell phones, this bag will work. Many of the long thin bags won't hold a larger cell phone. So that's a problem and one reason why I came back to this one. But I wanted a bag that I could also add some lipstick, kleenex and maybe even a tiny camera and there is plenty of room in this one. It comes in several nice colors. I ordered the silver. It's not shiny or garish. Just a nice fabric with a bit of sheen.

I also spent some time looking at small evening bags in stores and was not impressed with the selection. Again, many were long and skinny so a larger cell phone wouldn't fit. I kept coming back to this one and I'm very pleased with it. And yes, the inside is a GORGEOUS red color. So fun and happy.

column6: Women's Nike Revolution 2 Running Shoe Black/University Black/Hyper Grape/White Size 6.5 M US
column14:
Nike Women's Revolution 2 Blk/Unvrsty Bl-Hypr Grp/White Running Shoe 6.5 Women US- So alittle background on this story, my mom who is 67 yrs old decides it is time for a little vacation down south, buys airline tickets and and is ready to get the party started.
I am thinking to myself how the heck is she going to get through the airports and all the walking she will be doing is truly going to be unexpected exercise to her. No way the mom can make the trip in Bo Bo tennis shoes. I might add also that she has NEVER in her life owned anything better then a pro wings brand or even Wal-Mart el-cheapos for that matter.
So being the great son I am I got on Amazon and ordered her up a pair of these bad boys to improve her 40 time. All I heard from the time they were shipped to the time she received them was I didnt have to do that and she didnt need new sneekers. Regardless at 55.96 these black and purple streamlined bad boys were on the way. Now Im not saying the shoes improved her 40 time much but I can assure you she hopped off the plane and was moving with a purpose to the baggage terminal and all she could talk about was how great her new Nike's were and how good they fit. They hardly came off her feet the whole vacation and in the end I am glad she finally got a pair of good sneekers at 67.

column6: Jessica Simpson Women's Jasmint Platform Pump
column14: I really wanted a plain pair of nude platform pumps that looked great with any dress I'd wear. I've had many Jessica Simpson heels and they've all looked good and were pretty comfortable. These are exactly what I expected them to be. My feet are normal width and I wear an 8.5 usually but since I've noticed my other JS heels that were 8.5 started to get a little loose, I went with an 8. As with any shoes that are high, your feet naturally slide downward so "heel slippage" is a concern. They fit snug on my feet and my heel isn't coming out of them when I walk. The width is fine- it holds my feet in but it is tight (not uncomfortably so, just enough to keep you feeling secure in them). What I didn't notice was the seam that runs up the front of the shoe (see photo). I don't really mind this but others may want a more clean looking front. These heels also have a more pronounced point (see photo) than others of mine but I don't mind this either because I love the silhouette it makes from the side. The toe portion sits lower than others I've had so you will probably have some toe cleavage. I think Jessica Simpson heels look and feel great!

column6: HOBO Vintage Alice Wallet
column13: I thought this wallet was adorable and bought it to replace an incredibly durable and ...
column14: I thought this wallet was adorable and bought it to replace an incredibly durable and long-lasting Fossil wallet that I had been using for years and years. This Hobo wallet was functional for about 1-2 weeks before it started self-unloading all my credit cards and ID any time it was turned upside down, which naturally happens when it's carried on its own, rather than in a purse. The leather on the turquoise version I bought rubbed off within days and now appears so dirty and worn that I am embarrassed to take it out of my purse. I contacted Hobo customer "service" to see if they would replace the wallet with a different style that didn't dump all my cards onto the ground so regularly and they didn't offer any support of any kind. Basically, and I'm paraphrasing here, they  just said, "yeah, we know our products don't last. Nothing we care to do about that. Buy another one." I have gone back to Fossil and get lots of compliments on that wallet. Long review short: If you need a cute wallet that will last between 2 days and a month, maybe this is for you. If you're looking for style, solid design, and durability, then check out Fossil or Frye.

column6: Small Beige Genuine Leather Crossover Body Handbag
column13: Living proof leather doesn't have to be heavy
column14:
Beautiful, very light, and deliciously easy to carry. But with one drawback. It's so small that you can't put much in it. For example, one eyeglass case in the topmost (and largest) pocket will crowd out the other pockets. In fact anything you put in it will make some of the pockets unusable. Also the two tiny pockets at the bottom of the front won't contain even a single car key. On the positive side, here's what I've found it especially useful for: 1) Shopping in cases where you're going to be carrying heavy things (like groceries), want hands free, and don't want additional weight hanging on your arm. This bag easily holds the same items that in colder weather, I would carry in jacket pockets to the same end. 2) Slipping into carry-on luggage on an airplane for use at your destination. Ideal for that. 3) Stuffing into a desk drawer that's already "full."

I wish some company would also make larger bags out of lightweight leather. Who wants to drag around something that weighs 2 to 4 pounds without anything in it with the manufacturer's excuse that all genuine leather is heavy?

column14: I purchased this wallet with framed coin pocket a few years ago and have been using it hard ever since. It is most definitely a woman's wallet, meant for a purse, not a back pocket.  It works with American money, euros, or a combination. It is as tough as nails and since it is a tri-fold it doesn't take up a lot of space in your purse. The framed coin purse is extremely practical for dumping coins in without having them fall  back out. There are two compartments for bills, so you can keep paper money from different countries separate, or just keep your large currency separate from your small currency. The wallet has seen heavy use and still looks like new. I plan on buying two this Christmas for female relatives. Why anyone would think this was a men's wallet is beyond me. Too bad for the men, this works great!

column6: Salomon Men's XA Pro Mid GTX Hiking Shoe
column13: No longer waterproof after one hike.
column14: These boots were purchased for me about a month ago and I've worn them a total of three times. Twice around the office to wear them in and once for a hike up Mt. Katahdin to really test them out. Total mileage of about 15 miles. While they were very comfortable and looked great, I noticed that there was a hole on the right boot's toe box where the stitching had come apart after the hike. It's right where the rubber meets the fabric where the toes bend. I contacted Salomon customer support and was notified that "the damage was the result of normal wear and tear." So they're telling me that my $170 "fully waterproof hiking sneaker" is rendered no longer waterproof after one hike up to Baxter Peak. Buyer beware. This seems to be a common issue with this particular boot.

The wingtip style with a Doc-type sole (but MUCH lighter weight) gives it a distinctive look. The leather is relatively thin (but not cheap) and the shaft is nice and soft, so no chafing. The boot runs about 1/4 size large, so there's room for a good cool-weather sock, or for your foot to swell a little on warm days or when you're on your feet for hours. I have a narrow foot and the boot fit me well in my regular size. And speaking of size--on one website, a European 40 equalled a 9, on another a 9.5 (for this shoe). I wear a 9 in most shoes, and, as I mentioned, this seems to be about a 9 1/4. Your mileage may vary.

The boot has a full, knit lining and a lightly padded tongue. Appearances to the contrary, the midsole & sole do not have much give, but the boot seems pretty comfortable. I often wear an arch support orthotic, but I'd need a bigger size boot to fit it, and they seem to top out at 40, so oh, well. And speaking of arches--the side zipper is useful for getting the boot off, but my high arches mean I have to unlace it to get it back on. Oh, these first-world problems!

A previous reviewer said that they toe of the boot looks bowl-like, but that's not my experience at all. It's tapered and much more refined than a work boot/Doc Marten equivalent. The wingtip is pretty subtle, but you can see it, so you get the best of both worlds with plenty of space for your toes, both side-to-side and top to insole. (To contrast, I had to buy my BedStu Bonnie boots 1/2 size larger because the top of the shoe pressed down on both big toes like an anvil.)

All in all, the only negatives I have for these boots are the lack of cush in the insole and the thinness of the leather overall--I would have liked a little more substantial boot, frankly. column6: Sof Sole Fit Performance High, Neutral or Low Arch Shoe Insole for Men and Women
column14: Sof Sole has some of the best inserts for the price and I'm a big fan of the lower arch version of these inserts, but I thought this might be helpful to "High Arch" folks: I bought a pair of Chaco brand shoes (specifically the "Hinterland" model - See Amazon Link: http://amzn.com/B00AR3DE44 ) for hiking & everyday walking. It was my first pair in that brand. They had that "golf-ball in my shoe" arch feeling from the moment I put them on. I don't need that kind of arch support and after an hour in them (just walking around the house), I was in agony. I was prepared to return them to Amazon, but I remembered that my neighbor had mentioned his arch/custom insole issues several times. A few days later I took them over and explained why I was returning them and asked him to see if they fit him and if the "golf-ball" was helpful in his case. He came over the next evening and went on and on about how great they were. He asked if he could buy the ones I had and where could he get more of that same brand. I sent him the link and two weeks later he told me he had bought three more pairs in various styles and what a fantastic find they were. He said they are the first ones he's owned in years that he could wear without his custom orthopedic inserts. So I gather all the Chaco brand styles must have that same arch support characteristic as well. I thought this insight might be helpful for others with similar arch support needs-- and that sharing my experience would serve some purpose. Again-- I know very little about the brand and there may be something critical that I'm unaware of; so please do some research before you buy anything. I just know that Ted next door was almost in tears over how great they were for his orthopedic issues and I felt obliged to share it in case it's useful to anyone with similar issues. Best Of Luck!

column13: Nice Bag, but Description Dimensions DO NOT Match the Actual Bag Size
column14: Something doesn't jive with the description of this purse and what I actually received.  The pictures are accurate, but I have to wonder if the written description is for another bag.  It is NOT alligator embossed leather.  Just regular pebbled leather texture finish.  The described dimensions of 14" wide and 12" tall are not accurate either.  The actual bag is much smaller than that at approximately 11-1/2" wide and 9" tall.  From the description I was expecting a larger bag and really would like it better if it was larger.  It would likely be fine for many ladies, but I tend to carry extra "stuff".  The firearm pouch is just fine.  Holster is secured by velcro and holds the gun in place well.  The snubby revolver I carry fits with room to spare and the zippers are plenty adequate for drawing it easily.  Quality of the leather is good and it appears to be well-made.  My only issue is with the overall size.  Too bad they don't make it in a larger size.  I carried it for a day or two to see how it would work, but it's just too small for my needs, so returned it and will look for something just a bit larger.

column14:

My only issue with these shoes is that they are not water resistant at all and I work in an environment that can be wet at times so I can no longer wear them to work. I usually wear these without socks just in day to day casual wear. They can easily go into the washer to be cleaned.

column14: First shoe I put on and never felt the need to "break in". They were comfortable off the bat. I've worn Clarks flip flops and have sworn by them since I was about 15 years old. I no longer have to wear white tennis shoes for work, so I was happy to be able to find a very high quality navy shoe. I'm pleased with this shoe's performance. I tested them a few days in a row putting them on in the morning and not taking them off till around bedtime just to see how comfortable and I was happy with the results! column6: Mephisto Women's Brebina Gladiator Sandal
column14: I am a size 8.5 and, being new to Mephistos, first bought an 8 when I fell in love with the picture of these on Amazon.  My toes hung over the ends, but one trip around my living room in them convinced me that I HAD TO HAVE THEM in the right size and would pay any price for them, including $280 (holy cow).  So I returned the 8s, and the 9s came a couple days ago. Usually a 9 is too big on my narrowish foot, but with the back strap being adjustable, I was able to make these a perfect fit.  Besides the good looks, great fit, and feeling like I'm walking around on puffs of whipped cream in them, I am thrilled with the stability of these sandals.  I have weak ankles and have fallen and broken bones twice in the last six months due to that.  My orthopedic surgeon told me no more backless shoes, no more Crocs (WAH!), no more soles and/or heels with rounded sides--they have to come straight down so if my ankle buckles, the shoe will stay flat on the ground and not let me fall.  Mission accomplished.  Too bad the butternut color isn't available in a 9.  I'd snap it up in a heartbeat, even at $280.

column6: Starbay Brand Men's Athletic Water Shoes Aqua Socks
column13: They are also not comfortable. The sole of the shoe is very thin
column14:
I used them once for rafting, and the insole (which was supposedly glued in) came off and began sliding around inside the shoe, causing sand and grit to get under the sole and rub against my feet for the duration of the trip.

They are also not comfortable. The sole of the shoe is very thin, so if you're walking on a rocky area, prepare for pain. I had to wear these as we walked through the woods for a short time, and I could feel every single rock poking against my feet.

The mesh also allows sand to get in and rub against your feet. I don't imagine a lot of people would like that, either.

However, they are cheap. If you need some semi-disposable water shoes you'll only wear once, you might want to consider these. They went in the dumpster after I got into my dry clothes, because, obviously, I couldn't return shoes that had been worn in the river.

They loosened up and felt great on my second trail run of 4 miles. They have excellent traction in mud, dirt, rocky terrain, and wet terrain. I would definitely recommend these shoes to anyone looking at strictly trail running or for both hiking and trail running!

column13: The Phillip Tall Harness is my favorite tall boot I've found
column14:
As someone with narrow feet/ankles and smaller calves, I can have a hard time finding tall boots that fit right. The Phillip Tall Harness is my favorite tall boot I've found. I got a pair in black about three years ago and have worn them at a number of conventions where I have to walk all day. While I do always use at least a small foam insert, they are one of my more comfortable boots for cons. The only shoes I have that work better are ones that are specifically designed for comfort like my Birkenstock sandals or Clark ankle boots.

I actually recently got this boot in burnt red too when it went on sale. If you always have trouble with boots being too big, especially in the ankle, give these a try! I bought my normal size and could fit a thin insert in, but if you want to do a thicker insert or heavy socks, maybe try a half-size bigger.

column13: New convert; these are a nice non-athletic minimal shoe option
column14:
Well satisfied with these for the price. My first pair of this style of shoe. I am a convert to minimalist shoes and these certainly fit the bill. Yes, they have a strong chemical odor, which I am sensitive to. I was satisfied that it was acceptable after I aired them in the sun for two days. I still make sure they are shut up in the closet when I'm not wearing them.

I needed to make two adjustments for fit: first, I poked additional holes in the strap with an awl so that I could make them fit more securely. Second, I added the cheapest type of drugstore insoles for a little bit of additional padding. They are much more comfortable for me with that little extra cushioning (without it they essentially have none). No arch support or other support, which is what I want. Will buy more!!

They are a good bit slimmer than my last pair believe it or not.
I usually wear a 6.5 but was going to order a 7 to be safe, by the time I went to check out the last pair of 7's were sold, so I went with the 6.5.

They fit perfectly for me. I won't be able to wear a heavy weight sock in them, but I usually only wear light weight to medium in a good pair of boots, so it isn't a problem for me.
I would advise ordering up half a size if you want to wear heavy weight otherwise you'll probably be uncomfortable in the toe box.
The thinsulate lining is well constructed with the shoe, and the fleece at the top opening is a nice touch.
They are a little stiff to get on and off, but they are lace ups, if you don't tighten them properly you won't get the right fit, so you must loosen them to get them off.
I suspect this will ease with time as they get broken in too.

I do like the toe box fit, and the fact that they snug to my ankle so well.
They also attach nicely to my snow shoes. So I think they will be a good combination together.

Being the avid tester I am, I wore them through the dew this morning and was pleased to see the water roll off.
They seem like they will hold up to their water proof claims and I have high hopes for how they will fair in the New England winter this year!

Keep in mind, these shoes aren't really for running or exercise--just fun shoes to wear around the house or perhaps shopping. Nevertheless, the cushioning and sole is thicker than I thought at first, giving more support than I realized.

The size ordered (10) fit as expected.

As shown in the video, the set also includes a class-looking carry bag.

column6: Eagle Eyes ClipOns Navigator Sunglasses
column13: BUY THESE ... YOU'LL LIKE THEM and THEY'LL SAVE YOUR EYES
column14:
I own and use 2 pairs of these: one in my "man bag" and one in my pick-up truck. I do not go out in the sun without them. They definately protect my eyes and clip over may glasses well. If you are a slave to fashion and don't care much about really protecting your eyes... you may care more when you become a senior citizen! Protect your eyes now to enjoy for the rest of your life! :-)

When you put on Eagle Eyes the first time and every time you wear them is vision that sees much more detail and every image in more sharp detail: the glare reduction allows you to see much more detail of clouds, buildings, traffic situations, wildlife, ... everything, without the reduction in light that you'll get from the grey/green sunglasses.

You will be stunned by your increased abliity to see much more detail with Eagle Eye blue-blockers Put them on, and give yourself time to adjust to the bronze tint, and give your eyes a few minutes to try them out!

Eagle Eyes are great in low light situations, or in broken light situations. With grey/green you will not get as much light and you just won't see as much. In fast changing broken light situations, or in low-light situations you will be able to see more with the blue-blockers. However, if you are driving thru a tunnel, I recommend removing your sunglasses regardless of whether they are blue-blockers or not.

The glare redution from these glasses allow your eyes to relax and enjoy the day. I'd advise wearing a hat to protect your head with a broad visor to cut glare even more. Try Sunday Afternoon wide brim hat. The wide brim will cut the glare even more, and you'll protect your eys, head, face and neck from harmful solar radiation.

Eagle Eye sunglasses come in a very nice bag that and a very nice semi-hard case with a zipper to help you protect your sunglasses when you are not using them. Eagle Eyes has a cleaning kit available, also, with an anti-fog/cleaner spray.

column6: New Balance Women's WO99 Multi-Sport Shoe Shoe
column14: Last year, I bought these in a size 5.5 W as that is my typical New Balance size. They were too snug until I replaced the inner removable footbed with a much thinner one. They now felt very comfortable, and had great traction on hikes. Unfortunately, the mesh over the toe area recently started to develop holes. I tried stitching them, but more holes appeared; very annoying since everything else was still in great condition. I have a difficult time finding shoes that fit, so with much hesitation, because I thought the same thing would happen again, I ordered another pair, this time in a 6W. This pair fits fine with the footbed that came with it. Time will tell how well the upper mesh holds up.  Update: After just 3 walk/hikes, holes in the mesh area over the toes began to appear. AAARRGH!! Fortunately, I was still within Amazon's 30 day return/refund window. I was especially annoyed as I was in the middle of a hiking vacation in Acadia National Park. I have great difficulty finding comfortable shoes in my size and so felt doomed to carry on with these holey ones for the duration of the vacation. But alas, the stars aligned. While waiting in line for the ladies' room, I noticed the hiking shoes the lady in front of my was wearing. They had rounded toes and looked like the shape that tends to fit me. She told me they were Merrell's Moab; I figured I would look for them when I returned from vacation, but there they were in my size in a little store in the little town where we were staying. I got them in 6B (they do not come in wide), and they were comfortable right away. Hallelujah. So, if you have somewhat wide feet like mine, I would recommend that you give the Moab a try - Amazon has them.

column6: New Balance Men's M940V2 Running Shoe
column14: I'm not a runner, but a few years ago my arch hurt, so I changed my everyday sneakers to running shoes. I do bike and use an elliptical trainer in them and sometimes play basketball. I wore Asics 2160s at first and liked them and they had a nice wide 4E that fit my wide foot. Every year though, Asics changed the shoe in some way and I had to find the new model that I liked best. They changed so many times, I didn't even like the shoe anymore. I had to find another brand and shoe. I spent a lot of time at a running store with multiple brands and sizes and settled on the 940V2 in a 2E. These shoes seem to be the approximate width of the Asics 4E and are super comfortable. They fit my needs perfectly and I like how they look. One side benefit...I have had hard bumps/callouses on the instep of my right big toe for a long time. I had given up on getting rid of them. In the shower a few days ago, I noticed a marked improvement and I had not even done any treatments recently. I immediately used my file to file it down and then sand it and it is almost 100%. New Balance, please don't change this shoe!

column13: And the winner for best shoes for hospital workers is: Sketchers Go Walk 3!
column14: I love these.  These are my second pair of Sketchers Go Walk 3s, and I swear by them.  I have chonic pain, work 13 hours a day on my feet in a hospital, and these are the first shoes in 10 years that have made a difference.  I briefly think every new shoe I try helps- Danskos, expensive sneakers, orthopedic inserts, etc., but then I find either the pain comes back or a new, worse pain has started.  These shoes are so light you barely notice them, yet support you in ways you didn't know you were missing with other shoes.  They aren't the cutest thing, but there are more and more people at work wearing them. My joints certainly hurt less than usual after a shift, and I even felt less upset that I hadn't gotten to sit down in over half a day because my hips were feeling pretty okay for once.  These are a little cheaper in the stores, but I got them on Amazon day so it was worth the deal.

column14: I purchased this purse in the Khaki colors and can't say enough good things about it! The woven brocaded fabric is REALLY PRETTY. The faux leather accenting looks and feels like real leather (soft and thick). The feathers are a nice touch too. The bag is roomy and big without being overwhelming. It has a few pockets inside along the purse wall and two, deep outside zip pockets on each end. I read all of the reviews before I ordered and there we're only a few complaints‚Ä¶One woman sent it back because the lining was unruly. When I got mine I could see where the lining material might want to come up and out with what ever you were fishing out of your purse. This was an easy 10 minute fix. I just threaded a needle and tacked the lining to the bottom in 4 places, perfect. The purse comes with a longer shoulder strap that can be used over the shoulder or lengthened to use as a cross body strap. One reviewer didn't like the longer strap because when she attached it she didn't like the fact that it connected to two smaller rings and it left the bigger attachment holes for the other strap dangling. The fix for that is to run the longer strap and hooks through those holes and hook the longer strap in from there. I did that and it looks perfect. This is a beautiful bag, goes with anything, summer or winter. I sprayed mine, strap and fabric too with Scotch Guard to keep it looking nice. I highly recommend this item!

column6: Teva Men's Wander Low-Top Canvas Shoe
column13: Look great. Appear to be well constructed but sizing will be a problem
column14:
I have slightly full feet but I have always been able to offset my "tall" feet by ordering a 1/2 size up. This has worked for me for decades with sneakers, boots, dress shoes and sports equipment (skis and hockey skates.) With the Wander Lace Canvas I eventually settled for a size that was a 1/2 size larger and a full size wider to fit in them comfortably.

This shoe is really tight in the mid-foot exuding a painful pressure at the base of both "pinkie toes." I can offset this discomfort with a medium-weight sock but I bought this shoe with the purpose of wearing it casually- With shorts and a light, thin low-profile sock. Nope, not with these puppies. After a half hour wow, my dogs are barking! It feels like someone wrapped one of those lobster claw rubber bands around my foot. All I want to do is take these things off. It took me two resizings to get the fit to work.

Conclusion: These shoes look great offering a perfect casual flair to shorts but without the arrogance of Bass Bucks or the peppiness of Sperry Topsiders but sizing will be a challenge if you wear a D size or wider and/ or have full feet. Buy them but be prepared to send them back for a new size.

column6: Crocs Gianna Link Ballet Flat
column14: I started a new job at the front desk of a hotel so I'm on my feet all day long. When my mother in law suggested that I try and find some crocs, I cringed. I got a pair of cute flats and wore them for three weeks while getting blisters and trying to break them in, but my feet were still killing me at the end of the day everyday. I saw these on Amazon and I decided to give them a try because I was desperate. I've been wearing these for two and a half weeks now and my feet haven't hurt at all. They're ridiculously comfortable. I don't even think about how long I've been on my feet anymore. The first time I wore them to work I immediately got 3 compliments on how cute they were. I'm very happy with these shoes. I didn't have to break them in and they never gave me blisters! I have high arches and my feet typically hurt after wearing flat shoes, but these shoes have been amazing. They are kind of small and if I order again I might try and go up a half size if it's available, but they're really not bad and I've hardly noticed. I HIGHLY recommend these shoes to anyone who has to be on their feet all day but has to have more "professional" looking shoes.

column6: Sof Sole Airr Orthotic Full Length Performance Shoe Insoles for Men and Women
column14: These are great! I was a bit skeptical at first. I have a pair of the heel inserts and the arch area in these is not as firm. I was afraid this would be a problem. It is not! I put these in my athletic shoes and have been wearing them every day/all day. I have plantar fasciitis and flat feet. My feet have not felt this good in over a year! Are they cured? No! Are they still sore at the end of the day? Yes, but it's more tired than sore. And they don't ache up to my knees and my ankle isn't hurting. This is major! I have tried many different inserts and these are, by far, the best. The only negative that I would say is this...they fit in my athletic shoes just fine (size 10). However they are too big for any of my other shoes. These were not the shoes I had planned to use them in. There is no template on the insoles for cutting them down and, more importantly, no indication if they are made to be cut down. I'm not sure if they will tear up if I cut on them so I'm afraid to do so. The insert itself, nor the packaging indicates whether they are made for this.....

column6: Ektio Men's Breakaway Basketball Shoe
column13: Great shoe. Beware or durability. Quality control problems
column14:
I'm giving these shoes a generous 3 stars because, for the 4 games and 6 practices I got to play in them before they broke, they were one of the best shoes I've ever played in.

The good:
- True to size (9, Runs a little wide, which fits me perfect)
- Low profile (great for a point guard like me)
- Good stability vs weight (very stable/not heavy)
- Great lock down

The bad:
- Insoles are bad and need to be replaced
- Straps are way too short, which makes it impossible to wear additional ankle support or even an extra pair of socks
- Straps break easily
- CUSHIONING COMPLETELY FAILED IN RIGHT SHOE AFTER WEARING TEN TIMES

As you can tell by the all caps, the last negative aspect of the shoe is what did them in. I can't wear them at all. The left shoes is still function fine, which makes the defect in the right shoe that much more glaring.

Great shoe. Too bad I can't afford to buy another $100 pair every 2 weeks ($2400/yr). Ultimately I would not recommend this shoe because of the durability issues.

Lastly, I contacted Ektio directly today about the issue. I will update my review filling their response.

column14: I am returning these. I ordered an 8.5, with the expectation that it might be a little large (I think they use Italian sizing, different from European?). column14: I have been looking for a Velcro closure shoe I can wear to the gym, but I have hard to fit feet.  One is bigger than the other due to a healed fracture, and both have very narrow heels and B-width toes (duck feet in other words).  I tried another Mephisto All-Rounder and was very disappointed in it, had to return it.  So browsing for another pair of Velcro Mary Janes to try, I could not BELIEVE the price on these, and also they are much cuter than the ones I sent back--so I had to give the All-Rounder another shot.  Glad I did.  I could adjust this one to a perfect fit for both my feet. And it's about as cute as these Velcro Mary Janes gets (except the Dansko Hadley, which is too nice for the gym).  So this little Mephisto Sprint is a real bargain, everything you should expect from a Mephisto, and worth three times the price.  I say go for it!

column6: ECCO Women's Biom Lite Speedlace Oxford
column13: In my search for a comfortable, supportive
column14: In my search for a comfortable, supportive, lightweight walking shoe that isn't bulky, several brands have been tried and returned. FINALLY, this shoe is perfect. column6: OluKai Kupa'a - Men's Casual Shoes
column13: These shoes are AWESOME! Totally worth the price
column14: These shoes are AWESOME! Totally worth the price: High quality genuine leather, VERY solid treads, and the arch support is awesome. It was like walking on a cushy carpet.  CONS:  That said, the toe section of the shoe is oddly wide, so much that when I laced them up, they scrunched up pretty heavily and made for a somewhat painful wave in front of the laces. My mom said: "They look a little clown-shoe-y". In fact, this was only on the left shoe. The left and right shoes actually seems to be different widths.  I sent them back because of this.  Additionally, the site says "order a half-size larger". DO NOT.  I normally wear an 11, and thought "My feet aren't growing anymore, I'll order a tight 10.5."  Well, the 10.5 still left over a thumb of length inside. I should've ordered a whole size down to a 10.  If you order these, try ordering a half-size smaller - as they seem to run a little bigger and wider than you might expect. Otherwise an extremely high quality shoe that I think will last a LONG time.  FEATURES: As for the folding heel thing to make them into slip-ons?  It turns the shoe more into slippers. They don't feel very secure wearing them like that, even laced tightly. The shoes are quite light but still have enough weight that it feels really odd to wear them like that.  I'm going to order a size 10 and see what I think. I really want to keep these.  UPDATE: ordered a size 10 (half size under my normal) and they fit PERFECTLY. The toe area I still think is a little wide, but still extremely comfortable. High quality build again, will definitely have these a while. Treads are awesome too.  Con: the drop-in heel is interesting, but it's a little stupid. They aren't comfy enough to wear barefoot with the heel dropped in, and having a socked heel sticking out the back looks awful unless you're wearing brown socks.

column6: HOKA Huaka Ladies Running Shoe
column13: I like the way they fit (I ordered in my regular ...
column14:
The Huaka is as close to a zero-drop shoe as Hoka makes. I am switching between Altras and Hoka Stinson Tarmacs, and I thought I would add the Huaka to the mix. I like the way they fit (I ordered in my regular shoe size) and how breathable the uppers are. There is plenty of room in the toe box (although they are not as wide as my Altras) and my heel seats well. They come with speed laces installed, but they also have a set of regular laces.

My problem with the Huakas is the midsole. While it has some give, it is much stiffer than the Hoka Stinson, which in turn is not as "squishy" as either pair of my Altras. With my plantar fasciitis issues, the softer ride really makes a difference, so I'm afraid the Huakas will be going back.

column6: Merrell Jungle Moc Frosty Waterproof Slip-On Shoe (Toddler/Little Kid/Big Kid)
column14:
Purchasing Merrell Jungle Mocs has become an annual ritual in our house. Both my girls consider them "must haves" for the new school year. More recently, we've started to purchase the Frosty waterproof model. My ten-year old is drawn to puddles and these mean that she can walk through them and still stay dry. Each pair lasts a year which is saying a lot. They are used for everything and are their favorite shoes. They seem to provide great support, they are easy to slip into on your way out the door and they are nice looking. my husband has Merrell hiking boots and raves about them too. I've always thought they made great shoes, but I feel even more strongly now. I'm ready to get my own pair.

This year I bought a pair for my older daughter that were too big on her. I tried them on and they were perfect. I never thought about getting a pair myself, but I'm loving them. They are so easy to put on and so so comfortable. I can see that I will want a pair every year too.

column6: KEEN Men's Newport H2 Sandal
column14:
Unfortunately, where I live the terrain is quite pebbly, whether on dry land, on the shore, in stream, lakes, rivers or the ocean. This leads to accumulation of pebbles in the sandal which are very difficult to remove with the closed toe and raised edges of the sole. I actually have to take the sandals off to get pebbles out. I would expect to do this with a boot but I rarely pick up pebbles in a boot; on the other hand it is happens all the time with sandals.

One would think that they would make great water shoes, however, pebbles raise their head again - I feel I am constantly having to take one or both shoes off to clear the pebbles.

column14: ok, now like most people, i presume, i don't like buying clothing/footwear from the internet.  you just never know how things are going to fit.  i'm particularly fussy about footwear.  well, i like the look/style of these boots, and read most of the reviews.  the reviewers are spot on with these boots.  not only are they stylish, (in my opinion), but they fit like a glove and are very comfortable.  i just got them and put them on, and said to myself, "yes...YES YES YES"!  they are true to size, and my feet are a bit wide, so i got the 2-e width.  they are plenty roomy.  i don't usually take the time to type reviews on-line, but others had, and it helped me in making my decision, so i thought i'd, "give back" a bit, and let potential buyers know that i highly doubt you'll be unhappy if you purchase these boots.  i intend to wear these boots almost daily.  no "break in" is required.  they are not stiff, and you can wear them all day right out of the box.  i hope red wing continues to make these just as they are for many years to come.  but, in case they change the style, or discontinue them, i'm buying another pair right away.  just a quality product here, folks.

column6: Bates Men's Reyes Motorcycle Boot
column13: The first time I wore these was on a 2,100 ride.  Rain, hail, 111 degrees. (10,000 + miles wearing these now)
column14:
The first time I wore these was on a 2,100 mile ride (probably not smart, but do everything at the last moment). I rode from Upstate New York to Southern Tennessee. I went through low 50 F degree mornings to a heat index of 111 in the South with rain and even hail. I wore these shoes with wool liner socks the whole time. They were great and much more comfortable than I ever expected (although obviously warm in the South, but not too bad considering).

Good grip on road services when you stop even in wet conditions.

These fit true to size and have a lot of arch support (I have high arches and these are great).

Unsure about long term quality, it is questionable, I will update this review later as to how long they last long term.

+++UPDATE 08/10/2017 : I have rode probably another 9,000 miles with these boots on. I love them, I would buy another pair if Amazon had my size. Still holding up great and compare to much more expensive boots I have purchased.

column14:
Oh, I love this shoe! ...and hate writing reviews...that is how much I love this shoe.
This is my second pair. I wore the first pair every day...winter and summer. Due to several foot surgeries, I must be very choosy about my footwear. I wore Danskos for years, but the Alegra Classic replaced the Danskos because the Alegra Classic actually decreased my foot pain. I can only think it is the rocking design and solid structure that strengthened my feet. There was another surgery in my future, but that has been put it off indefinitely. Now for the one small CON... I have to say...they are UGLY. (That's it...nothing else.)
Bottom line/Summary: Because the Alegra Classic improves and heals my feet I will wear a not so pretty shoe....every day, rain or shine, winter or summer, at work or in the garden.

column6: Powerstep Pinnacle Maxx Full Length Orthotic Shoe Insoles
column13: Pinnacle Maxx OK, but regular blue Pinnacle is still the best
column14:
This is a quality insole. But, for someone looking for good arch support and an insole that isn't too thick/bulky in your shoe, my absolute favorite among all insoles I've tried is the regular Powerstep Pinnacle (blue color). I've bought and worn both Powerstep versions, because I wanted to see which would work best for me. And, IMO, the regular Pinnacle is a thinner insole than the Maxx, not surprisingly, but also feels like it has a somewhat higher and more supportive arch support element.

In other words, my feet feel OK when I put the Pinnacle Maxx in my shoes. But my feet feel really great when I put the regular Pinnacle blue version in my shoes. And, I should add, I'm a guy who's 6-8 tall and about 275 lbs. So, if I'm getting good support from the regular Pinnacle, it's hard for me to imagine who's going to need more support than me with the Maxx -- unless for some reason, you just want a thicker insole in your shoe. As far as cushioning and comfort is concerned, I didn't find the Maxx to be superior to the regular Pinnacle at all.

column14:

I was disappointed because they just didn't work. The length was fine, the instep fit well, but the insole was so, so narrow - my foot just hung over the edge, so whenever I walked I could feel it digging into my arch. Additionally, the silver accent part (along the side and the heel) is actually made of plastic, and it arrived a bit scratched up.

So while they would have been comfortable if the width had been right, they just didn't work for me. I don't know if narrow is the hallmark of the Onex brand, but I might not order these online again unless I can try them on in person first.

column6: Five Ten Men's Guide Tenie Canvas Approach Shoe
column14: I found these shoes to be, simply put, great. They have amazing grip- that Stealth rubber has incredible ability. I've used them on mountaineering routes amd sending some low-fifth class pitches. One thing I didn't consider but is fantastic is how easy they are to take on and off so you can save some time and energy while switching in and out of climbing shoes on route or at the crags. I chose canvas because I thought it'd be more durable in the long run compared to leather, but this has ghw drawback that they get rather hot. This doesn't bother me personally but it might bother some people. The canvas is fairly resistant to some exposure to mud and water but in a rainstorm or heavy water on trails or routes I wouldn't expect them to be keeping my feet immune from the elements. They feel much more comfortable after some breaking in. Overall, a very affordable approach shoe that does not sacrifice performance.

I bought the Tommy one for 49.99  which is my second choice but it's very heavy empty and has three compartments divided by that stupid pouch in the middle. I'd don't have time to fight with my bag looking for random items. I love this slouchy style it's so bohemian and  European looking, but it should be as organized as possible. Got the blue denim one which I love by  it's casual so will be buying the khaki too. One to travel with, one for the gym, an one for everyday for my laid back office in a beach community in Southern California. column6: Birkenstock Women's Gizeh Thong Sandal
column13: Takes the flip-flop to a whole new level
column14:
I usually don't write reviews a few hours after the product arrives, but I've bought a lot of Birks the last few years, and I was really pleased with the way this pair felt right out of the box. Because it's now the middle of the hottest part of the summer I'm already used to the feel of the toe piece between my big and my second toes, and the leather seems more supple than it did in some of my others when I first got them. The box says "Habana, Waxy Leather." I don't know if the waxy leather is different from the oiled leather or not. I have two pairs of black oiled leather sandals that were pretty stiff when they were new, although they're now fine. But the leather in this pair is much softer.

Anyhow, these are comfortable right out of the box for me. These are my first pair of Gizehs, and I love the look. I have high arches and really need the support that Birks give. The color is a natural looking dark brown with just a hint of red.

And one more word about the sizes. I wish Birkenstock would start warning people that their footwear runs large. I wear a size 9 in the US, a 40 in most European shoes, but a 39 in Birks. If you've never bought them before, go in a local store and try some on til you get the right fit. It could save you some grief.

column6: New Balance Women's WW515 Walking Shoe
column14:
I bought these mary-janes because I suffer from severe arthritis in the ankles and laced up shoes, even when loosely tied, cause too much pain and pressure. The straps on these shoes are long enough, with an easily adjustable "Velcro" attachment.
The toe box is wide and high enough. The shoes are also lightweight. Altogether they are more comfortable than lace up walking shoes, but the arch support is inadequate. I had to add a cork insert. It makes a big difference, but it is not the same as having the arch support as part of the shoe.
I haven't had them long enough to know about their durability and how well they fare in wet weather.

(No weird peek-a-boo foot spots that throw off the fluidity of the design.) I bought these in black, size 7.  The top calf strap circumference is 13" when the strings are completely pulled closed--but, they can be opened throughout to fit larger calves.  The foot insole width is 3", but the straps expand a bit outwards to fit a slightly wider foot.  The insole length is 9 5/8" to the very tip.  The foot-bed is a bit tapered, so you might need to size up if your foot is longer then 9.25" or of wider width, or else your toes will look crammed.  They are of a sturdy construction, comfortable to wear, and the tassels give it a nice finished looked.  They are extremely elegant and eye-catching, they do not look cheap or trashy.  Get these!

Great with baseball and driving caps. The polarization is really good. It puts some interesting colors on the world sometimes, and comes off as mirrored in direct light, so a very cool effect.

So here's the fun part. I took these on a trip to the Caribbean, and they withstood a ton of abuse. Wore them in the ocean for nine days straight. Accidentally bent the frame in my fist diving into the water, and they bent back into perfect shape. Got hit by a wave while swimming another time, and they ended up in about 15nfeet of water, so I went and rented a mask and snorkel to go get them from the bottom. They were fine. Through all this, I only rinsed them with clean water until the last day when I used a little camp suds to wash them. Bent them again while they were stuffed in my backpack on the trip home, but easy to fix again.

Great sunglasses.

column6: La Sportiva Men's FC ECO 3.0 GTX Hiking Boot
column14:
Thanks to the Backpackers Shop, and trying on 7 different types of light boots, these were the winners. I'm fascinated that people think these are narrow. Asolos...those are narrow..for me.. My foot is on the way to being flat and while it isn't as wide as the Renegades, they still weren't causing any pressure like normal narrow shoes do. That's the tricky part...feet...everyone's feet are completely different. I had originally bought Oboz, and was in love with the style and how rock solid they felt, but THOSE started causing pain from narrowness, and the heel sole/heel area was so rock hard and stiff, every step I would take I could feel my brain rattling. No shock absorption at all...but even with that, I would still rate those 5 stars.

I was able to get a 10.5+ size which is fantastic. 10.5 was a bit tight and my toes were almost touching...The 10.5 + is perfection...or whatever reason.

These are extremely comfortable boots. I can't say enough about the comfort. It reminds me of the old Merrells I had. They felt like pillows on my feet.

Haven't used these outdoors yet...I can tell the sole will have exceptional grip...will probably wear out fast since there isn't a ton of tread width...but I'm sure I'll get a couple/few years out of them.

Bottom line for EVERY boot/shoe.. They will fail, they won't last forever and they will wear out faster in some areas...I accept that. These should last long enough to get my money's worth.

column14: I have arthritis and a very long foot (13 medium) so I have limited options. New Balance has been my everything shoe: black ones for work, other colors for weekends, and my fave has been the 847. Then the 847s started going away in my size, leaving me with the 847v2. This is the first and only New Balance shoe I have returned, and I have bought many. It feels very tight on my left foot, and the overall support and comfort of the shoe was very poor. I would never have guessed this was a shoe made by my beloved New Balance. The quality also did not seem as high, though of course the price is still as high as ever. It seems NB is moving away from made in america as well, which set it apart from a lot of the competition. I am exploring other options and I am willing to pay more for quality, good fit, and made in the USA. That used to be NB.

column13: Snazzy and comfy in the rain, anywhere, anytime!
column14:
I was looking for a pair of "riding bootie" style rain boots, and this pair is absolutely incredible! Elegant, sleek, comfortable and really snazzy! I use these for looking cool like a cucumber when walking my doggies in the park, where it can get muddy on the trail. And - yes, that's almost too much! - I even wear them in the garden, after a good rain drenched all my veggie beds. Hey, there is no reason for me not to look hip even when trudging around in some mud! A good rinse with the garden hose, and presto! All is shiny and pretty again in no time!
Of course, they would also look fantastic in the city streets, when it rains! I may try that the next time, too! The interior is fit with a soft fabric, and the opening of the boot is widened by releasing the belt buckle. They fit perfectly, as 10 is my regular size, and they fit to a T.
The price for these simply can't be beat, either!
I love them!
If you liked my review, please let me know! Thanks for your time!

column6: InSassy AC Adapter Power Supply Cord for xBox One - Replacement Charger Accessory Kit with Cable - AC 100-240V 4.91A 50-60Hz
column13: Why is there a loud fan in the unit? Returned...
column14: I was skeptical about this, but based on some reviews, decided to save money and go for it. I want a second set of plugs so I can move the Xbox from living room to bedroom without reaching behind cabinets. First, I read the label and compared to the OEM for Microsoft, and noticed this seemed to put out 1.5 more amps than the original, 17.4a v. 16a. Don't know much about electric stuff, but made me cautious. Then I plugged the unit in, and the fan started, and it was SOOOOO LOUD!!! What!?! After 5 seconds it shut off. Then I turned on the Xbox, and ten seconds later, the fan started up again. Oh my, this is weird because the OEM power brick has no fan. I scan the menu, watched a little bit of NFL through the Xbox, then shut the system down. The fan kept buzzing...and buzzing...and buzzing. After 11 minutes and then some, I didn't start tracking until 10:23am and at 10:34am, I had enough, and unplugged the unit, back into the box and returned. Looks like I'm paying for the original.

column13: I should've assumed this game wouldn't of been good considering the makers of the first Spider-Man super hero ...
column14: I really wish that there was never a product of The Walking Dead that I rated poorly. But ya know what? This game deserves it. First off, I should've assumed this game wouldn't of been good considering the makers of the first Spider-Man super hero games making a zombie game wouldn't of been good. The game is way to short, and not even good. You survive. You find Merle within an hour and the next 2 hours you just go from place to place to survive. The pre Oder said it came with a ear keychain. It was a printed out picture... You can't get cheaper man. The game wasn't advertised through the tv show during commercials (you can obviously tell why) it's so cheap, graphics aren't good at all but not (omg this is such crap and it brings the game down because of it) it's just horrible for a 2013 game, but not unplayable. You can peak Round corners pressing LB but the game didnt tell you that. You had to figure that out yourself. The games so short, and a cliche ending that's not even good, I've seen cliche endings before and at least they can be good. This wasn't horrible, but it wasn't good at all. Not bad at all, but not good. I beat the game within 1 day. Less than a day actually. This game should be free eventually through games with gold on Xbox, considering how bad it is and they will save money other than them giving a actual good game away for free. It's kinda cool you meet Andreas's parents. But tbh, that was the highlight of the game for me...

column6: Just Dance 2014
column14: I have been dancing to the Just Dance Wii games for just about a year now. Last June I decided to finally get in shape and lose some weight. Knowing how much I detest exercising I knew I needed to find something that I could stick with in order to achieve my goal of losing 40 pounds. I grew up in the 80s and was a video gamer through and through so when I saw there was a video game that included dancing and music, I had to try it. I purchased Just Dance 4 as my first one. It was great so after that I purchased Just Dance Greatest Hits, 2014, and 2015. In my opinion they are all great, some better than others.  The songs are also great. You get a real mixture of genres so most everyone can find songs they enjoy dancing to.  I just wish Nintendo would release more DLCs and more frequently. I was able to lose those forty pounds by last October and almost a year later have managed to keep it off and maintain using Just Dance and a balanced diet. I am so thankful for these games because if it hadn't been for them, this gamer would probably still be forty pounds heavier and vegging out in front of a different kind of video game. Thank you UBI Soft and Nintendo.  I am including an after picture and a picture of all the clothes that I donated because they didn't fit anymore.  Thanks to Just Dance and following a balanced diet (logging everything into the Lose it! app daily) I was able to lose the weight.

This WONT work on windows 7 or 8. (That is some folks online have managed to get it to work, but from what I can tell it's a great deal of trouble ). The sell doesn't go out of their way to show this information, and it's not worth my time to return it (that's what they count on).

column6: Fosmon AC Adapter Power Supply Cord for Microsoft Xbox ONE (Output: 150W, 12V 10A) - Includes Charging Brick & Cable with US Plug (Input: AC 100-240V)
column13: It's great to be able to purchase a back up power ...
column14:
It's great to be able to purchase a back up power supply so easily. We spend soooo much on our gaming systems nowadays. It's also nice to have back up cables for taking the system traveling. Needless to say, I am quite pleased that I was afforded the opportunity to review Fosman's AC Adapter Power Supply Cord for XBOX 1 in exchange for an unbiased and honest review. In the package you will get the power supply, with one detachable power cord.
I have quite a few Fosman products. I have always been happy with them, fortunately. I don't know about your TV set up, but we have multiple systems hooked up to ours, along with the cable box. It's not that convenient to disconnect everything. If we travel, and take a system with us to entertain our child, it's easier to unplug the system from it's cables and go. Much easier, if I may say so myself. This power supply is heavy duty. It's made well. It's well vented to prevent it from getting too hot. There are rubber feet underneath to prevent it fro sliding around or off the table, depending on your set up. It has built in LED indicator lights. I love having the LED lights on it, lol. I like to know when things are on and running, or not. Here are the specs on the power supply: Input: AC 100-240V; Output: 150W, 12V 10A. I couldn't find anything I didn't like about this product. I feel comfortable in recommending it.
I received thsi item in exchange for an honest and unbiased review.

column14: *** August 2, 2015 review update ***  I found my original 3DS XL stylus today - it somehow landed in the front pocket of my purse, a place I never thought to look for it since I'd never put my stylus there. Figures, right? lol Well, at least I still have these as replacements.  It should be noted that when I purchased this 5-piece set back in March 2015, the item was listed as:  "eForCity¬Æ 5-Piece Retractable Stylus Compatible With Nintendo 3DS XL"  It now lists "Insten" as the brand name instead of eForCity, but the product images haven't changed. Whether or not it's still the same set of 5 that I bought is unknown. Insten could be a re-branded version of eForCity, or it might not be at all. That could be the reason for some of the other reviews of people receiving something completely different than what's pictured, so, buyer beware when purchasing.  If you receive the stylus set as pictured, it's definitely a great quality set and one that I'd recommend if you need a replacement 3DS XL stylus.  If anyone wants specific pictures compared to the original, which I can do now, or if you have any other questions, feel free to leave a comment and I'll try to answer.  *** ORIGINAL REVIEW ***  I lost my original 3DS XL stylus, so for a while I used an old PDA stylus that I had lying around, but wanted something that would actually fit into the slot on my 3DS XL. A first party replacement from Nintendo would have cost more after shipping costs, so with this, I get 5 for less than the price of 1! Good deal.  These fit snugly into the stylus slot on the 3DS XL. I barely ever use them extended since the size of them when retracted is similar to the original 3DS XL stylus and that's long enough for me to use comfortably. I tend to only extend/retract them when I'm bored.  The tips on these are very smooth. No visible seams, and best of all, no scratches, so they're perfectly safe to use with the 3DS XL.  Overall, a great value and now I have four extras in case I need them.

column6: J Stars VS+ - Parent
column13: Where do we begin for one i already owned the imported version for the ps3 and sadly there wasnt anything new added to the game
column14:
im a die hard anime fan so dont get me wrong this review is clearly just based off this remake... Where do we begin for one i already owned the imported version for the ps3 and sadly there wasnt anything new added to the game other then a useless mode called arcade mode. no new maps, playable characters, support characters or items from the shop. It was legit the exact same game i bought 2,3 years ago.
Il start the review on a game aspect now. The amount of moves per person are disapointing there isnt nearly enough different moves before you realize your just pressing the same combinations over and over till every can preform a special then the ultimate special. The story mode is a joke there is some false claim of free roam that makes it seem like you can go and do what you want. With the same generation enemies that continue to float around no matter how many times beat them. Truthfully this game isnt worth the hype there is other games id much rather play. Like One piece pirate warriors series, even the naruto ultimate ninja games and the newest dragonball xenoverse. Plus the storys dont last longer then 6 hours so dont waste to much roaming around just do the objectives. Or youll waste time for a poorly made stories. theres 3-4 seperate short strories which are all pretty much the same unfortunately.
The games most focal point was suppose to be the online battles/ co op. which was completely broken with certain characters being way more over powered then others. Also find ways to continue a chain before you hit the ground like it was marvel vs capcom. I wouldn't recommend this game to anyone.

column13: I have played both motion heavy games (like Wii Sports Resort) and button heavy games (like Super Smash Bros) and had no issues
column14: I got this controller mainly because I have had an affinity for Afterglow controllers and their quality for a third party product. The controller works flawlessly with no problems. It gave me no problems when playing games on both the Wii and Wii U. I have played both motion heavy games (like Wii Sports Resort) and button heavy games (like Super Smash Bros) and had no issues with either. Not to mention that this thing glows really brightly and just as good as I expected. It is also compatible with Wii Motion Plus and fits regular Wiimote jackets. There are only two minor complaints about this controller which firstly is that the + and - button placements are different than the original Wiimote. The original has the buttons surrounding the home button in the center but are now moved higher on the controller surrounding the A button. The Home button has also been moved adjacent to the power button but that didn't bother me especially because I prefer that design better. The + and - buttons do take some time to get used to however. The second gripe I have with the this controller is that the safety strap does not have the clasp but rather the plastic slider. Not a big deal at all but I much prefer the clasp. For $25 though, and including the nunchuck, I would not only recommend this but buy it again.

column13: Disappointment even for a fan, awful split screen
column14: Wish I didn't have to give this game so low a score.  I'm a fan of several of the anime series featured in the game (Jojo, FOTNS, YYH, DBZ) and love playing as those characters.  Unfortunately, the story is dull and repetitive (I barely have the energy to get through 1 campaign let alone 4 all with characters I don't really care about) and there isn't much reason to keep doing it once you've unlocked all the characters you care about for the other modes.  The actual fighting is pretty wonky and is mostly just hitting the same buttons over and over until its time to block and repeat.  The worst problem with this game is the split screen multiplayer. 4 player split screen would be perfect for this game considering the matches are almost always 2 v 2, but the game only allows 2 players.  Adding a second player also makes the screens incredibly small, about the size you'd expect with 4 players in Halo for example.  As much as I like having a game with all these characters, this was a disappointment.

column14: My boys love this game so much! We already had it on the computer, but my two older boys really wanted to be able to play it together. So, we got this for them, and they love it so so much. I have strict restrictions on the amount of time my children play video games, generally 1 hour max per day. But, this is the ONE game that I often make exceptions for. The creativity I see when they play, with the amazing things they build and are SO excited to show me, makes me so happy! The calm, soothing music it plays instead of fast paced, quickly-becoming-obnoxious, loud music and sound effects that accompany most kids video games out there today. I actually enjoy hearing the music when they play and have been known to tell them that they can turn up the music a few notches if they like!!!  Also, the conversations between them as they play, as they talk about creating things, and how to create them, and think of new ideas... it's just refreshing. I never thought I'd actually enjoy seeing my kids be so involved in a video game, but Minecraft is SO different.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column13: I really wanted to love this game but I kept asking when will this end.
column14:
Ok, I know I'm going to get bombarded by the fanboys and downvoted but I just can't pander to anyone. It's not in me and the game should have been miles better than it turned out to be.

I played through the PS3 Arkham games, including Origins, which was lackluster and doesn't really count in the trilogy and was more a cash grab than an actual cohesive game. My expectations were pretty high for PS4's Arkham Knight. What did please me was how the game looked and the story. That's about it.

Where to begin? First of all, the gameplay. Batman can do everything he does in the previous Arkham games. The problem is, they designed the missions so that you are forced to do what they want you to do, as opposed to before, you could basically choose how you want to attack the path you're on. They decided to add a lot more gadgets to Batman's collection, which on paper sounds cool, that is until you're going through the daunting task of hacking into a blimp's controls to tilt it and clear the path you need to follow, or using a voice synthesizer to open a gate or distract guards, or blinding flying drones or turrets, so you can take out the guards around. They made it needlessly more complicated, seemingly for the sake of it and the slowing down of Batman is not a very welcome concept, at least to me.

Also, it gets frustrating how often you die and have to re-attempt the missions. The drone tanks (and especially the cobra tanks) and the gangs of baddies have been seriously amped up in difficulty. Particularly when it you get to the siege of GCPD near the end, expect to want to throw your controller into the TV, and then of course remember how much money it costs and just hit the wall instead. The upgrades help but it will take quite awhile to get enough so that it makes a big difference. Not only do you have categories of upgrades but you also have levels of upgrades on top of that and you have to buy this upgrade to unlock these upgrades. It's sofreaking convoluted!

Once you finish the main storyline, it isn't actually done. There are also a large number of side missions and in order to unlock the game's finale, you have to complete a number of the side missions. I finished the Own the Roads side missions, or so I thought. I did all the ones marked on the map but now I have to "find" the rest of the locations? Now I know why it was a mistake going further than the ending in the first place. Come to find out, there are actually 2 finales. You get to see one if you finish 7 of the side quests (which means all the missions within each side mission string). If you want to see the ULTIMATE FINALE, then you have to do 100% of all the missions. Nuts to that! I mentioned how annoyingly convoluted this game is, didn't I?

When I finished Arkham Asylum and Arkham City, I actually felt compelled to do more side missions because the play through was fun. Definitely not the case here. I really wished I could get into this but I left the experience exhausted, frustrated and not the least bit excited about how the rest was going to turn out.

Edit: Ok first of all, I forgot to mention the Batmobile. It is super clumsy, handles really rough and is a pain to use. They made it so that you have to use it waaaay to often. The Riddler missions where you are racing are super frustrating and I know I mentioned the drone battles but let me elaborate. It gets really difficult to defend yourself against tanks that shoot missles, tanks that shoot cannons in 3 different directions and flying drones at the same time, especially when they are in great numbers and it's in waves, meaning, you destroy one group and think ok, I'm almost there but nope, they replenish their numbers about 3 times. It's impossible to complete the harder ones of these until you've fully upgraded the Batmobile's weapons and gadgets, which like Batman's upgrades, will take awhile. Another super annoying thing about drivingaround, even when you're on a mission, is running into cars and people constantly. All the cars have bad people, so when you get close, it triggers a mini-mission, which will override what you're currently attempting to do. That happens also when you're not in the Batmobile. If you have a waypoint set and are following something or someone, you will constantly be bombarded by surveillance of people talking and it will confuse you by telling you how far they are and take you off track from your goal.

Now, I don't know why, maybe I'm a glutton for punishment but after taking a break from the game after finishing the main storyline, I decided to go back and do more side missions. They are easy enough when you first start out but then start to get super hard as you get toward the end of each. That's not my main problem though. For some reason, it doesn't give you all the locations. As you clear a bunch out, you have to search for the rest of the waypoints. I've now reached the point where I've completed almost enough to unlock Knightfall protocol except one and for every mission I have left, it tells me I have to look for them. So that's how they reward all the work you put in? You have to go looking for everything? I think I'm really ready to put the game back into my shelving unit for good again and looking up the endings on youtube.

column6: Generic Battery Pack Cover for Xbox 360 Controller
column14: We recently bought a Xbox 360 secondhand. One of the controllers would not work with the battery back cover it had due to battery corrosion. I searched online on ways to clean the corrosion out and got most of it clean. Unfortunately there was one contact that I just couldn't get clean enough to make the controller work. I knew it wasn't the controller itself because based on a YouTube tip of how to put batteries in without a cover, the controller worked fine. Minus that it kept disconnecting during for my son due to the batteries getting slightly jostled while he was holding it, even with it taped up. I checked Amazon for battery cover replacements and voila! It was cheap enough to give it a try. It came within 2 days (thanks Prime!). I inserted the batteries and snapped it onto the controller and we were in action! It works as it should. It fits our controller perfectly. My 3rd child can play with his siblings without getting upset that his controller doesn't work. Saved me the cost of buying another controller.

column6: Microsoft Xbox360 Wired Controller Microsoft
column13: 2 / 3 controllers did not have a USB port
column14:
I had bought 2 of the these so a friend and I could play a game on our computer together. I was excited to set it up, but it took an hour of tinkering around with random settings to get it to work in the first place. I ended up following the direction of 3 youtube videos until one worked. Something about the drivers not updating properly and I had to manually set the controller to pick the correct driver (which was downloaded from microsofts website) in the services application.

Finally, I got it to work and gave it a try with a few steam games to make sure it worked. Happy, I set the controller aside and waited for the weekend. I quickly unwrapped the second one and put it in my backpack along with my laptop to head over so we could play. I unwind my controllers to find the second one didn't have a USB port... it only connects to an XBox!
Did I order the wrong one and was lucky enough to have 1 good controller? Or was it an infuriating blunder that was made on their end? I'm pretty sure the latter since many other reviews say it works fine on the computer.

Unfortunately the game we wanted to play did not support 1 keyboard and 1 controller user.

I dropped a star because the drivers were not easy to figure out for someone that isn't the best with computers.
The other star is actually how comfortable I am with controllers(tried it out on another game). Perhaps it will grow on me over time, but I prefer the feel of a Playstation controller. I like both analog sticks to be at the bottom. Unfortunately they're more difficult to set up than XBox Controllers. My comfort is a personal preference though. I normally wouldn't knock a star off, but having to deal with returning and ordering another one still has me peeved. Half star for each.

Update
I couldn't get the adapter cable to work, my computer doesn't recognize what it is. I didn't want to bother learning how to fix yet another piece of hardware that doesn't work out of the box. I just spent 10 hours getting a mouse, the first controller, and a drawing tablet to work on my laptop. So, I ordered another controller. I checked the back of the box, and it shows an image of a USB port. Again, this one does NOT have a USB port, and it doesn't not come with an adapter of any kind. This is the second time I've been burned ordering from here, and it won't happen again. I may as well just go to a gaming store the next time I have a chance so I can see the thing before hand.s getting a mouse, the first controller, and a drawing tablet to work on my laptop. So, I ordered another controller. I checked the back of the box, and it shows an image of a USB port. Again, this one does NOT have a USB port, and it doesn't not come with an adapter of any kind. This is the second time I've been burned ordering from here, and it won't happen again. I may as well just go to a gaming store the next time I have a chance so I can see the thing before hand.

column6: The Order: 1886
column14:
This game had a lot of potential and I thought the concept was very neat. I also am a steampunk fan. Third-person shooters are a good time as well as I always liked Gears of War. The Order 1886 consisted of nothing but a huge letdown for me.

It seems like 75% of the game consists of boring cutscenes that you can't skip. It almost is like one of those lame movies your teachers made you watch that you had no way of getting out of watching. I am fine with some cutscenes if they actually are more than people yacking for 20 minutes and are fluid with the flow of the game. That's not the case at all here.

Aside from the cutscenes, there is some basic platforming thrown in. This will consist of about 15% of the rest of your time. The remaining 10% is actually action and shootouts. Not only is this obviously disappointing for a "shooter" game, but its also even worse because the shootouts are a pain in the neck. The camera angles suck. The game does have a decent cover system even if it is borrowed from other games like Gears of War. I don't mind that, but when every time I get hit while shooting I get thrown out into full stance and have to re-do my cover, what is the point? Isn't the point of cover when you get hit to be able to stay in cover and not start all over again?

I am just glad I rented the game. That and the graphics were the only good parts of the game. I was really hoping to like it, but in the end, I decided after a few hours that it felt like I was getting robbed of time trying to continue to play this frustrating game. It's just not enjoyable at all.
