column6: Zero Escape: Virtue's Last Reward
column13: Visual Novel and Puzzle game guaranteed to pull you in and never let go.
column14:
Please note that this game is the sequel to the DS title "9 persons 9 hours 9 doors". Virtue's Last Reward will spoil some of the big reveals of 999, so if you plan to play that game, please play it first and then play this title.

Without giving anything away about the plot of VLR, I will say that it is an incredibly deep story with a lot of surprise twists and relentless intrigue. Often I had my theories reduced to ashes by one bombshell after another, and very rarely did I call something before it happened (and boy does it feel good to predict something in this game). The game is not all visual novel, though. Half of the game is about escaping a room by solving the puzzles contained within. Every room features unique puzzles covering a broad range of subjects from math to riddles, to three-dimensional puzzles and code-cracking. There were a number of rooms that had me scratching my head, but often all I needed was to take a break and come back to the game later.

The puzzles are not the only interaction you will have in the game however, during the visual novel, you will often get opportunities to dramatically alter the course of the story through choices. The most important example of this is a 'minigame' called the 'Ambidex Game', or 'AB Game'. Unlike the previous title, the nine persons in VLR are all working towards a very important end-goal - to collect a total of nine 'bracelet points' or more. By doing this, a given person can open the number 9 door, and they and anyone else with nine or more points can leave the prison the participants are trapped in and escape. Anyone left behind is trapped forever. Because the storyline can be altered, there is naturally a lot of different endings to achieve (including a good number of 'bad ends'). If you ever feel like you made a mistake, or you simply want to try something different, the game has a built-in flow chart that you can access at any time, and use it to 'jump' to different chapters in any point in the game you've previously been through. This way, you can jump back to before a crucial decision and change your mind, or jump out of a puzzle room you're stuck on and start a new path in a different storyline.

Moving onto the participants and their goal to escape, I should briefly explain how they earn the points necessary to escape. To earn points, the participants have to play the AB Game, where the participants choose between two options: to Ally with the last person they chose to join forces and solve a puzzle room with, or to Betray them. The incentive for both options breaks down like this: If both parties choose to Ally, then both parties gain 2 points toward their bracelet point count. If one party votes Betray, however, the traitor(s) will gain 3 points, and the ally will lose 2 points. If both parties vote to Betray, then both parties are locked in stalemate and do not lose or gain points. Each of the 9 participants begin with 3 bracelet points, and if they fall to 0 or negative bracelet points, or break any of the rules imposed on them, they are instantly executed with a lethal injection from their bracelet.

This AB Game is based on the 'prisoner's dilemma', and is just one of the few concepts this game explores. Sometimes the storyline delves into intense scientific theory and investigation, but thankfully the protagonist is more of a Watson than a Sherlock, and asks almost all the immediate questions players may have when exposition kicks into high gear. So even if you have never heard of something, you can be sure you'll have a grasp on it soon enough.

I could go on and on about the cast, but to even begin would be to open the floodgates to a large reason why I love this game, and risk spoiling things for the uninitiated. Simply put, the cast is diverse and infinitely interesting. You will never figure each member of the cast out in the first meeting you have with them, and just when you think you know them, they'll reveal something about themselves that you wouldn't expect. Sometimes you will be shocked, sometimes you'll be furious, and sometimes you'll love the characters even more.

Buy this game. If you love games with a strong cast and a story that you can't help but immerse yourself in, then this is one title for you. If you've never played any of the Zero Escape games, then you should consider also playing 999.now them, they'll reveal something about themselves that you wouldn't expect. Sometimes you will be shocked, sometimes you'll be furious, and sometimes you'll love the characters even more.

Buy this game. If you love games with a strong cast and a story that you can't help but immerse yourself in, then this is one title for you. If you've never played any of the Zero Escape games, then you should consider also playing 999.

column6: MLB 15: The Show - Parent
column13: One of my best purchases of all time. Including my purchase of my AeroPress coffee system! I threw my Keurig & Mr. Coffee away!
column14: I just got my MLB 15 The Show today from Amazon. This is my first purchase of this baseball series. I have not bought a baseball game for any of my consoles since World Series Baseball I & II for my Sega Saturn over 14 years ago I think. That baseball series from Sega was awesome and my best to date. So last week I bought for $10  RBI 15 from the Sony Play Station Store. The graphics are sub par for what I expect of todays consoles for a baseball game. The overall feeling I got out of RBI 15 series was just ok but nothing special. I think I will take it off my PS4 to make room for a new game soon.  Now comes MLB 15 The Show and I have to agree with all the reviews I read. This game is great to look at and plays super. This game is superior to the RBI series game easily! The visuals are super and the players are very detailed. I showed my girl friend and she asked what Baseball game I was watching? I told her I was playing a videogame of a baseball game and she was like................ No Way! Wow they make them look so good now. I agreed with her and told her I am impressed with this game. I mentioned of lots of reviews on this game and that I bought this game a bit cheaper for the Anniversary edition. Because Amazon had other distributors selling this game. So this 10th Anniversary version was priced the same as the regular version on the Play Station Store for about $38.97. and this usually sells for $50 there. I am very happy with this purchase. Even the practice sessions as a pitcher or hitter are awesome to play. I spent at least 3 hours in the practice mode. So I could learn the timing and where to look for the sweet spot to swing the bat. My eyes are not the best now that I am 53 and believe me I used to be good at swinging at baseballs on videogames. Well not anymore and this game was a joy just to practice that. I give this game a 5 star rating!  And LaTechNmore props for selling me this game just as they advertised for much cheaper than other places wanted! Update 8/16/2015. I have had a few weeks to play this game. I played a little over a week the practice batting and pitching modes. I wanted to make sure how to judge and hit the ball plus learn the varieties of pitches. So today I started my first season playing. I am so amazed on the camera angles and visuals on the graphics. The players have facial expressions that the cameras catch and the announcing gives this video game a 95% feeling of being a real game!!! I cannot understate that remark that this game feels like a real game!! I bought Mega Baseball for the Xbox1 recently. While visually that game is cartoony, the mechanics of the game is very good. But Mega Baseball on the Xbox1 cannot compare visually or anything else for that matter.  The Show MLB 15 has blown me away that every time I play I see something new. Even the errors while I don't personally like my team to make errors. I'm thinking wow this game even makes mistakes realistically! I watch baseball now rarely compared to when I was in my early twenties ( I'm 53 ). But this game keeps me from playing any of my other games I recently purchased. Godzilla, Driveclub, Project Car, and Mortal Kombat X, and Shadow of Mordor. But I am happy to do that when a game not only looks but plays superior! For once I have to give it to Sony for putting together a masterful work of art! Sony has made little if any effort in making first party software for the PS4 this year. That is very odd considering the PS4 cannot do any wrong. The PS4 continues to dominate the console wars since the PS4 launch. At the very least Sony could pump some games of it's own into this cash cow system! Bravo for MLB 15 The Show!

column6: 2x Xbox Thumbsticks for Xbox One Controllers (Fits PS4 Thumbsticks for Dualshock 4!) by OneSoul [Black]
column13: Beware, you may get cheap, non rubberized ones.
column14:
I ordered these because I just do not like the feel of the PS4 sticks (all stick tops should be concave, not convex).

So I got them in and they felt really nice. The tops were completely rubberized and had amazing grip.

After about 10 minutes of play I noticed the left stick was rubbing on something. Long story short, one of the sticks base was slightly warped and it was rubbing on the underside of the top of the controller.

I really liked how the stick felt, so I figured I would just order another set and return these.

Well, got the new set in today and while they LOOK the same, the new ones are not rubberized AT ALL. 100% CHEAP PLASTIC! Absolutely ZERO grip to them. They feel like sticks you would get if you bought one of those knock off controllers in a 99 cent store.

The funny thing is, they knew they were sending me cheap plastic sticks because they included rubber grip tops. Bright PINK rubber grip tops.

So looks like I will be playing the Amazon lottery and continuing to return and order more of these until I get two of them that are what they advertise.

I saw another review here stating he also got cheap, non rubberized sticks. So beware folks, it really is all luck whether you get the good ones or not.

column6: Godzilla - PlayStation 4
column13: With Patients This is Something Special for a Diehard Godzilla Fan
column14:
I bought this well after reading many reviews critically panning this game, and expected to get a few laughs out of a terrible game, and then stick this on a shelf with the rest of my Godzilla media and let it be. However, I am having a lot of fun with this game. It has it's flaws; Movement is weird at first, graphics are middling, and the game is repetitive. At first, I was pretty unsure about the game, as I played through one complete cycle of the game as Godzilla. As I played through another, more familiar with the controls, it was a bit more enjoyable, and then again after leveling Godzilla up was even more of a blast, and then I played through as King Ghidorah, whom I had unlocked, and the play style was different, and incredibly fun.

I think this game has many flaws that will make it a terrible game to most people, but it really does play like a Godzilla movie. As a huge fan of Godzilla, that is what you want, to fight monsters like in the movies. I've played and love Godzilla Destroy All Monsters Melee and Godzilla Save the Earth, but they were fighting games first more than anything and you never really felt like you were fighting the other monsters like in the movies. This game pulls off the weight and feel of being a giant monster so much better, and it is so much fun when a new monster shows up that you haven't fought.

I think there is something special here for a hardcore Godzilla fan. If you are looking for a great fighting game, this isn't one, but I think it is a great Godzilla game. I'm looking forward to unlocking the other half of the monster list I have not encountered yet, and giving them a run.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Recon 30X Chat Communicator Gaming Headset - Xbox One (compatible w/ new Xbox One controller), PS4, PC, Mac, and Mobile
column13: An affordable to chat with your teammates
column14:
Attention: this headset is only compatible with Xbox One controllers that has the audio controller adaptor with the 3.5 mm stereo input jack. If you do not have an audio controller adaptor (a small device that allows the game controller to accept other brands of headphones) you can buy one on Amazon for approximately twenty-five dollars.
Turtle Beach has produced the economical Ear Force Recon 30x headset for the hardcore or casual gamer alike. Although, by design, this headset cannot offer the player an immersive game experience like other models they do provide clear and distinctive chat with volume control and mic mute. The generously padded ear cup is very comfortable and slotted to allow the player to hear the game audio from the television. This is a great headset for chatting with your teammate but, as previously mentioned, you will need to hear the gameplay on your television's speakers, so married, late-night gamers might want to invest in more expensive models that can broadcast both gameplay and chat through the headphones for the sake of not disturbing one's spouse's beauty sleep. With that concern voiced, I would recommend this model for any team or land party players.

I was using a wireless mouse for gaming and was getting bad lag on games. I had a decent system and felt that shouldn't be. Somehow I learned that wireless mice can cause issues, so I bought this. I played borderlands 2 with NO problems the day I installed this. And on top of it, I love this mouse. Will buy another if I need to in the future. Just to be clear I wrote this about 14 or 15 months after purchase. The thing still kicks ass.

column14:

column6: ASTRO Gaming A40 Audio System - Xbox 360
column14:

Overall I am happy with the quality of the sound, which is the reason I bought it.
I personally had a bad experience, with getting over 4+ faulty Headsets before I finally got one that worked. The 3 after my original purchase were all replacements, so there was no charge for me. It was very annoying and unlucky, but that's not a common issue.

column6: Batman Arkham Origins
column13: An average Batman game that you can skip over.
column14:
*sigh* I'm a bit disappointed with the overall presentation of the game itself. For the most it has an upgraded combat style that the previous games had, yet it was inconsistent with its own continuity when they made this as a prequel to the Arkham games.

1) The story is a big build off to an empty climax that went 0 to 60 & someone decided to use the emergency brake halfway there in order to end the game. I honestly thought a bit better from WB Games, but I can't be bothered. Don't play this game without playing the others, in fact don't play this at all if you didn't like what you read at the beginning of this bullet point.

2) I didn't find as many problems as people reported, mostly due to having the lastest updates installed. However, I did find some frame drops (lag), some freezes in random points in the game & a weird, yet funny animation quirk when knocking out a thug.

3) The multiplayer has aspects of the Assassin's Creed & Uncharted one which really baffles me in a way. I stopped playing it after realizing that & that some unfair balancing issues will make you play with unfair & overpowered opponents.

In conclusion, don't get this if you want to start out the Arkham games, if you want a better experience check Arkham Asylum & then City. You really don't need to play this game unless you want to see a ruthless Batman otherwise leave this game for another day.

column6: Onechanbara Z2: Chaos - 'Banana Split' Edition - PlayStation 4
column14: This game is a guilty pleasure. Males from age thirteen to thirty will find everything they could possibly want in this raucous romp: scantily-clad anime girls running around with katanas and chainsaws murdering zombies by the flesh load. Perhaps the best part about this game is that it is completely honest about what it is, which is no doubt reflected in the sub-60 dollar price range, $40, if you download it on the PSN. The game doesn't hide the fact that it is an over-the-top murder-fest with busty anime girls in cowboy hats, swimsuits and lolita outfits panting and huffing and puffing as they hack and slash their way through hordes of zombies and outlandish-looking bosses. Despite the fact that the game would no doubt make Anita Sarkessian have a heart-attack, there is a surprising amount of depth in the game-play.  Each girl has their own myriad of weapons and move sets and the ability to switch between the four girls in the middle of combat adds a new element of strategy (yes strategy) when confronted with enemies who won't go down by the typical method of hack and slash. There is a wide variety of modes with challenges that range from easy to surprisingly hard that unlock extras such as items, weapons and new outfits (or lack thereof) for the girls to wear. Level design is mundane and straightforward and most of the graphics have been reserved for the girls themselves with most of the zombie and boss models looking like they would be more at home on the Wii. The soundtrack is as catchy (and annoying) as and STD and you'll be surprised as to how many times you find yourself coming back to this game for its over-the-top and explosive combat, g-string and all.

column6: Minecraft - Xbox 360
column14:
I was excited to be getting this game. I've heard a lot of good things about it and I love the freedom of sandbox games. When I first started playing, I was having a lot of fun, but that fun turned into boredom just a few days after getting the game. From what I had heard and read, Minecraft had tons of things you could do and lots to explore. Although I'm sure the PC version has this, I wasn't very impressed with the Xbox360 version. With this version, your world is limited. This didn't bother me at first because I had heard that, although it was limited, you still have a big area to explore in. In fact, I kinda preferred it to be limited because it was so easy to get lost. Well, after getting the basics down and getting to know the area around my house, I wanted to start venturing off, exploring, gathering new materials, etc. only to find that this so-called "limited but large" world is, in fact, not large at all. After just an in-game day and a half, I had completely circled the entire map/island and explored all that could be explored. The map that was generated for me only had one small village, and after two in-game days, they were all dead from being unable to protect themselves from monsters. No temples, no dungeons, no pig men, the absolute only thing of interest was the small, now-dead village. From looking at the achievements, I saw that there are 23 possible biomes, yet there was only 5 in my map(Desert, jungle, grassland, plains, and alpine?). It even took forever for horses and donkeys to start spawning!

Because there were no villagers left, I was forced to start a new game. I haven't done much in this new game, but after just a little bit of exploring I found a good-sized town, a desert temple, and horses that were previously ultra-rare to find in the previous game, even after they started spawning. I'm hoping that first map was just bad luck and that most of the generated maps aren't so boring. If it really was just a fluke, I'll be much more impressed and change my review, but for now, I'm not all that impressed.

column6: Vortex Black Doubleshot backlit PBT + POM Keycaps - 104 Keycaps for Mechanical Keyboards (cherry switches compatible)
column13: I wanted to love it but...
column14:
So I bought the white version of these for my white cased Ducky Shine 4 and loved it so much that had to get the black one for my keyboard at work. Upon installation, I noticed that the molding for certain keycaps were not fully compressed, making it unable to fully latch on to the keyboard switch. So when it's on the switch, the key either gets stuck or you can't bottom out smoothly. Also, for the keycaps with numerals and symbols, the number does not light up but the symbol does. I think for the white keycaps, the light bleeds through a lot more so the numerals are able to light up. The black is more conserved, and therefore less bleeding in light.The original ABS Ducky keycaps has both the number and symbol lighting up. I can live with this, but I just find the lack of consistency of mere annoyance.

Fortunate for me, Amazon has a great replacement policy so I can easily swap out the defected keycaps. I just don't understand how my white keycaps were made without fault, but the black keycaps were poorly constructed. If it wasn't for the inconsistencies, I would've given this 5 stars.

column6: Zero: Nuregarasu no Miko
column14: A master piece of survival horror that is beautiful and use the WII U gamepad in a good way,  It's the story of 3 characters set in a moutain known to be a favourite suicide spot, Mount Hikami.  Yuuri Kozukata is a young woman that lost all of her familly in a car incident and since then, she sees the deads.  She was saved by Hisoka Kurosawa before commitng suicide.  After the incident she lived and work for Hisoka in her Coffee shop.  Ren Hojo is an occulitst writer and  is searching the death pictures that were taken century ago for a book.   He asked Hisoka to find a lost book and some photos got his attention.  He and his assitant Rui will help Yuuri to find Hisoka that dissapeared searching for a lost girl on mount Hikami..  Miu Hinasaki is a teenager in search of her long lost mother (Miku Hinasaki), she believes she is somewhere hidden on mount Hikami .  The story of the three will merge in this incredible adventure.  Pros : Gorgeous graphics, the WII U is pushing 1080p graphics on the screen and in the same time produce a great picture too in your WII U Game pad.  It's one of the few games where the WII U game pad is really usefull.  You use it as the Camera obscura.  This created the most fun ghost battle of the series.  The story is great  too and the characters likeable.  This was the longest Fatal Frame story, over 10 hours of gameplay.  And you don't need to beat the game on hard mode to see all the endings.  Cons: The game must be played on a Japanese WII U (well until they release the game in the west this fall).  The annoying over exagerated breast mechanic from Dead Or Alive 5's engine.  Let's hope they will reduce the bouncing as we can in the DOA5 games so it looks more natural.  I had notice some graphcal slowdowns in some scenes, but nothing game breaking.  Not enough  unlockable content  to add replay value.  So yes, I bought a Japanese WII U to play this game and I do not regret it since I can play all the WII Fatal Farmes games on it too.  Itotaly worth the price for me.

column6: Gioteck Ex-05S Universal Wired Stereo Headset
column13: Good durability, moderate sound, poor comfort.
column14:
I bought these relatively cheaply over a year ago, when I was getting ready to go to college so I could play video games and watch Netflix without bothering my roommate. I used it primarily for my PC, but tested it out on the Xbox 360 when I could - it works fine on that, too. No testing for PS3, but I presume the same could be said for that. For the $35 I paid, they served their purpose. The sound was nice, the mic picked up my voice clearly, and the ear cuffs had a fair bit of padding. Not the greatest headset in the world, but not bad. My only complaint is that the metal headbands feel like they're biting into you over continued use.

My first day, I tried them on and thought, "I'll get used to it," as the bands created an uncomfortable pressure right off the bat. It was either too loose or too tight, or too low on my head to cover my ears. After an hour, I did get used to it - but two or three hours left the distinct sensation that the bands were trying to morph my head to fit them, instead of adjusting to fit my head. The netting was alright, but it did nothing to distribute the pressure more evenly, to the point that when my roommate wasn't in the room I'd often wear the headbands around my neck or sometimes upside-down to avoid putting the bands on my skull again. The whole thing felt kind of heavy, which encouraged the around-the-neck listening with the ear cuffs vibrating under my jaw. This problem is probably on a person-by-person basis, as I have a relatively wide head.

I have to give Gioteck props for the quality, though. While I was worried about the joints at first, I quickly learned that there was nothing I could do to break them - including accidentally sleeping with the headsets under my pillow for a week or having them fall onto the hard tile floor in the middle of the night. The wires lasted through a year at a party dorm, though during the last few months I noticed a slight ringing that was alleviated when I touched the audio jacks - no idea what could've caused this, as the jacks were never plugged into my TV. The cuffs have a reasonable bend to them, though it will take some adjusting to see how they best fit on you. If you have pronounced cheekbones, you may experience some discomfort initially, but angling the ear cuffs back should help with that. If you wear glasses like I do, the sensation of pressure building up may get to the point of headaches, so I'd recommend either going without your eyes or wearing contacts if you have them.

It won't break on you. Aside from the ringing near the end, I have no complaints regarding the sound. If you're looking for a pair of headsets you can abuse, these are it; but if you're a stickler for comfort, I'd look elsewhere.

column6: Kingdom Hearts HD 1.5 Remix - Limited Edition - Playstation 3
column13: Maybe I'm just getting too old to understand the Disney references, characters, and convoluted storylines
column14:
Don't get me wrong, I'm a huge fan of the Final Fantasy series, so having never played the sister series Kingdom Hearts before, I was interested in playing it for the first time in this HD 1.5 Remix because I knew it has Final Fantasy characters in it. I played through up to the first half of the Alice in Wonderland quest before I stopped playing indefinitely.

To be honest maybe I'm just getting too old for video games, as despite having grown up seeing most of the Disney movies that the Kingdom Hearts series references, I could not understand the convoluted plot of this game at all. Also Kingdom Hearts is clearly not Final Fantasy, as the battle system is more action-RPG oriented, so that was a bit of a turn off. Goofy and Donald as AI controlled characters also appear to be abjectly useless in battle.

Maybe if I was younger I would have appreciated Kingdom Hearts for what it was, but alas, as an adult gamer I could no longer understand or identify with this series, which is a shame because I've heard good things about it, so don't let this one review dissuade you. However it may merit doing some research into the game, story, and mechanics before committing time and money to this series.

column6: Destiny
column14:
I recently decided to take the plunge and play Destiny. I was holding out for a good price, and also for my friends to get it as well so we could all play together. That was the right decision, as Destiny is a game best played with friends, but more on that later.

I've put in 98 hours and brought two characters up to level 32. I've only played the base game, not the DLC (which is not included in this disc). The first thing to know about Destiny is that it is an online only game. You will need a fast internet connection to play, and it is a good idea to have PS Plus as well, so you can play with other people. It is possible to play by yourself, but single-player quickly becomes boring.

The basic gameplay in Destiny is this: You create a custom character, go out into the world alone or with up to two friends and shoot aliens across four worlds, all while leveling up your character and finding better guns and armor. Everything you do in Destiny gets you one step closer to becoming more powerful. When you start, there is a 15 hour campaign that will take you from Earth to the Moon, Venus, and finally Mars. Each planet has about 6 missions, each one with a very basic story loosely tied to it. You start, a little exposition is given by your Ghost (a robot companion) and then a waypoint marker appears on your HUD. You go to that point, a little more exposition is given, and then you're tasked with taking out three waves of enemies or a boss, and then a short cut scene plays and the level ends. This same formula is repeated ad nauseam for the entire campaign. The story is, unfortunately, never more than your Ghost telling you that enemies are doing something bad and you have to kill them all to stop them from doing bad things. The only thing that keeps this all from becoming super boring is the enemy variety (which is about on par with Halo) and playing with friends. As a single-player affair, it quickly becomes dull. There is also a curious lack of vehicles, with only your Sparrow (similar to the Speeder Bike in Star Wars, but with no guns) and the Pike (an enemy Sparrow that also has guns), and in one level on Mars, the Interceptor (a tank-like single pilot vehicle with heavy weapons). 95% of gameplay is on foot, which is unfortunate since a larger variety of vehicles might have saved the game from a bad case of repetition.

Once you complete the main campaign, the game changes slightly. You still play through the same levels, but now how you advance is different. Before your character reaches Level 20, you earn Experience Points to level up. But once you reach the soft cap of 20, you now have to equip armor with Light Points to level up. In order to get this armor, you need to earn Vanguard Marks or Crucible Marks by playing the game over and over. It becomes a grind, but again, if you're playing with friends like I did, this shouldn't be a problem. Earn enough Marks, and you can buy new guns and armor from Vendors in the social space called the Tower. You can also find random loot drops from enemies that can provide you with guns and armor, but these are very unreliable. 98% of the random loot drops will be inferior to your current equipment, and buying equipment from Vendors is the only sure way to get the necessary Light Points needed to level up.

The point of leveling up is to tackle new challenges. Each stage in the game has a recommended level, and if you are at or above that number, the enemies should be a moderate challenge. If you're one level below the recommended number, the enemies will be much more difficult, and if you're two levels below, well, I hope you have life insurance, because you're going to die. A lot. You cannot take a mission more than two levels above you, and taking on a mission below your level does not make it exponentially easier. There is a damage cap, so if you're Level 20, a Level 3 enemy takes just as many shots to kill as a Level 19 enemy. As you get into the higher levels, there are Strike Mission, Heroic Missions, and Raids that will reward you with Strange Coins, Marks, Glimmer, and crafting materials all necessary for obtaining more powerful gear. And that is the cycle of Destiny. Play harder levels to get better gear so you can play even harder levels and get even better gear.

The controls in Destiny are rock solid. If you're familiar with Halo, the FPS mechanics are almost identical. I am a big fan of the gameplay in Destiny. It is tight, responsive, and fluid. I never once felt out of control or like the game wasn't responding properly. Both the campaign and the competitive multiplayer play fantastic, and everything from the feel of the guns to the dynamics of the player/enemy interaction felt spot on. Bungie is known for excellent FPS gameplay, and Destiny doesn't disappoint. There is a good variety of weapon types, each with a specific use in different scenarios. You have your primary weapon, usually a mid- to long-range rifle with a decent sized ammo clip. Then you have your special weapon, either the close quarters shotgun, the super long-range sniper rifle, or the mid-range fusion rifle, all with fairly small ammo clips and less frequent ammo drops. Finally, there's the heavy weapons, a mid-range machine gun (huge clip) or the rocket launcher (very small clip), both with very infrequent ammo drops. Since you can only carry three weapons at a time, the trick is finding the right balance of weapons to compliment your play style. I can honestly say, balancing issues aside, that there really isn't a bad weapon in the bunch. I tend to favor the Hand Cannon and Shotgun, but really I like all the different guns in the game and found them all to be useful at some point.

The graphics in Destiny are also a high-point. I've seen a lot of great looking games on the PS4, and I can honestly say Destiny is up there with the best. The game runs at a native 1080p/30fps and looks incredibly sharp. I've never been great at sniping on the older consoles, but in Destiny I can pull off headshots effortlessly with Hand Cannons, Scout Rifles and Sniper Rifles. I attribute this to the crisp resolution, which allows me to see the finest details even far off in the distance. The aesthetic of the game, from the character design to the distinct look of each planet, is well realized and executed. I never confused a fellow player for an enemy, and was able to keep my bearings even during heavy firefights. Even the technical side, like the lighting, textures, and ambient effects, is impressive.

Destiny is, as I mentioned earlier, an online-only game, and this presents a few issues that are worth mentioning. First off, you will need to buy a PS Plus subscription to get the full experience. Second, if you have any internet issues, this will impact your game, even if you're playing by yourself. I actually had a couple weeks where Comcast was working on the nodes in my area, and during that time I'd frequently get dropped from my game, even when playing by myself. The third is that other people's connections will have an impact on your game, especially if you're playing in the competitive Crucible mode. In Crucible I noticed a delay between when I'd fire and when an enemy would take damage, a delay that wasn't present in the Campaign. I'm not sure if that was my connection, or the other player's, but it seemed worth mentioning. But mainly it's unfortunate that there isn't an offline mode for those times when a stable internet connection isn't available.

The upside to having an online-only game is that the online functionality is excellent. Joining friends is quick and easy, and playing with a group of friends is a blast. Comcast issues aside, I never had any lag playing cooperatively with friends, and voice chat sounded clear. One player is the Fireteam leader, and it's quick and simple to start new missions, taking your friends along automatically, or assign a new Fireteam leader and let them choose your path. The interface is very user friendly, and matchmaking with strangers for those times your friends are offline is pretty darn fast. There isn't matchmaking for the 6-player Raids, though, which is unfortunate but understandable, as Raids require a level of communication and teamwork that strangers probably couldn't do. Also, each planet is filled with other Guardians (players) who are fighting enemies beside you in real-time. One of the best implementations of this are the Public Events. These are short, 3-5 minute events where an enemy ship will drop something and you'll have to either guard it, or kill a very powerful enemy before he reaches a checkpoint. Everyone playing in that area, regardless of whether or not they're in your fireteam, can join in and work together toward a common goal. It's a lot of fun to see lots of players working together for a few minutes.

The Crucible is the competitive mode for Destiny, and it's pretty good. There aren't very many modes: There's 3v3, 6v6, Control (King of the Hill), and a 12-player free-for-all. Beyond that, there's a few other modes that are locked behind a DLC wall. There is a decent number of maps, around 10 or so, but you'll see the same ones come up again and again. The good side of this is that you'll quickly learn the maps, which is essential to victory. Also, all of your weapons and armor carry over to Crucible, so if you have an Exotic weapon like Hawkmoon, Thorn, or The Last Word, you'll have a serious advantage. The negative side of this is that if you don't, you'll be eating a lot of lead. In fact, I'd estimate that at least 60% of my deaths in Crucible were at the hands of those three weapons. Even if you don't have Exotic weapons and armor, you can still have a good time in Crucible, and even if you lose you still earn Marks and gear, so you never feel like you're wasting your time.

The biggest issue I have with Destiny is just how boring it becomes by yourself if you play single-player. You can reasonably play through the 15 hour Campaign by yourself, but after that much of the game is just re-playing the same missions over and over at a higher level. Doing that by yourself becomes tiresome fast. This game really has to be played with friends to be enjoyed, but man, if you are playing with friends, it's one of the most fun experiences on PS4.

If you're buying Destiny for the Story, don't. It's worthless. But if you're buying to play with friends, you'll have a good time. If competitive multiplayer is your bag, you may want to look elsewhere, as what's here is a little bare bones. As for Bungie's 10 year plan, I'm honestly surprised I played for 98 hours, but I think I've squeezed as much juice as I can from what's on the disc and I don't see myself playing much more in the future. Bungie wants players to pay for DLC to extend the experience, and I just haven't seen anything compelling enough to justify paying what they're asking. When Taken King comes out in a few months, it might be worth checking out, but only time will tell. How much you'll get out of it will depend on how much you're willing to put in, both time-wise and money-wise. For now, if you have a stable hi-speed internet connection, PS Plus and a couple of friends to play with, Destiny is well worth picking up, especially now that it's under $30.

This game is really fun I would recommend it to anyone! You don't have to be experienced to get this game but enemies will get tougher as you process through the game. ( Typically after you've finished the story and they will be easier the more you level up.)
You will level up by completing tasks given by your life master, who guides you when you choose a life but they let you do your own thing, they will only hold your hand the first time you do a quest for them then on you complete them during your own time. ( Do not worry if a quest is too hard example; defeat a boss dragon to get to a spooky to move up to the expert rank. You don't have to this which is VERY hard, I got to expert wizard rank by going in caves completing expert-master challenge as a adept so do NOT think you must do quest X to get to the higher rank.)
You can choose what life you want there are ton of choices-forgive me if I forget some
(paladin, tailor, blacksmith, miner, carpenter, wizard, angler, woodcutter...) You can change your life at any time- as you will need "skills" in order to complete other people's requests in order to get 'dosh' (aka money in Reveria, the kingdom.)
I hope I explained this well (:

column6: Quickshot Model No. QS-126 Nintendo NES 8-Bit JoyPad Controller Quickshot #QS-126
column13: Maybe challenge yourself to see how far you can get in Super Mario Bros
column14:
This quickshot controller has a very strange design. The d-pad is a circle shape, but works the same way a normal d-pad would otherwise. The A and B buttons are on the upper left and right corners and the start and select buttons are combined into a single button which you push left or right. If there are games that require pressing start and select at the same time, this won't actually work. Otherwise it does function accurately, but is awkward to hold.

It's definitely for people who want to mess around with different controllers. Maybe challenge yourself to see how far you can get in Super Mario Bros. or do a game night where everyone has to use an odd controller to play some level like flight controllers or the Power Glove.

column6: Bloodborne
column13: So close, but yet so far.
column14:
Bloodborne is like that girl you've dated. You know the one; very attractive, great smile, nice frame, intelligent, but there's a certain aspect of her personality that really frustrates you and gets on your nerves. That fatal flaw is the one thing that's preventing you from falling in love with her, and taking the relationship to the next level. Some days, you feel like you're very close to falling in love with her, while other days; you question why you continue to tolerate her. You definitely like her, but you don't love her. So close, but yet so far... That's Bloodborne in a nutshell.

Combat - Bloodborne has the best combat I've ever seen. It's simplistic, yet complicated. The main attack buttons are R1 and R2, with L2 being used for the left-handed weapon. R1 can be used for a 'light' attack, while R2 is the 'heavy' attack. I enjoy the combat because it's quick and seamless, and there's not a lot of buttons to remember. Although you don't have to, I suggest locking onto enemies before attacking them; I found that to be easier than not locking on (mainly because of the camera). Bloodborne encourages and rewards aggressive combat, so it'll be in your best interest to 'be on the offensive' as much as possible, and here's what I mean by that: If an enemy hits you and depletes your health, you'll have a short window of time to attack them and replenish some of your lost health.

Weaponry - Some people took issue with the low variety of weapons, but I sure didn't. I stuck with the same weapon (Threaded cane) for the entire game. Now, if I had an interest in other weapons, there were some nice options available. I'm not sure how many total weapons are in the game, but I'm guessing at least 10 of them. There are a couple of ways to acquire weapons (for what it's worth, you'll start off with 3 to choose from, and you'll have to pick one). The easiest way is to acquire a badge that allows you to purchase certain weapons. You can acquire these badges by defeating specific enemies. The other way (the harder way) is by finding the weapons that are well hidden within some of the environments. Although I didn't use any of the other weapons, I still wanted to collect them all (trophy reasons), and I had to rely on my strategy guide in order to find some of them. For the people griping about the lack of weapons, I thinks it's important to point out that several of the weapons are 'trick weapons', meaning there are two weapons in one. For example, the Threaded cane can be used as a cane or a whip, and it's very easy to go back and forth between the two. If you're interested, you'll have the option to use left handed weapons such as guns, torches, flame sprayers, etc.

Enemies - Alright, here's where you'll definitely experience your first taste of adversity. No matter how weak some of the enemies may appear to be, they can easily kill you if you underestimate them. You may easily find yourself in a situation where you're getting close to the end of an area, and you're only moments away from the boss. You encounter an enemy type that you've beaten before, so you don't take him as seriously as you should, and a few combos later, you're dead. Why is this a problem? Unlike other games I've played, you'll have to replay the entire level because there are no checkpoints. If that's not adversity, I don't know what is. I don't necessarily agree with this practice, but it is what it is. The enemy variety is exceptional, and each area is guaranteed to introduce a new enemy type. If you enjoy a variety of bosses, it's very important to point out Bloodborne really delivers in that area. But of course, if a boss kills you, it's back to the drawing board, at the beginning of the level...

Miscellaneous - Online gaming lovers will be pleased to know there is an online component. I didn't try it, so I really can't speak to it. I do know you can summon another player for help if you're struggling with a boss. Thereare no missions or sidemissions in Bloodborne, for the most part. I actually liked this because I felt freedom to do whatever I wanted, in no particular order. I also liked that there were very few cut-scenes because I'm somewhat annoyed by a ton of pointless cut-scenes. I didn't do as much exploring as I would have liked because the absence of a map can make that a little tricky. Speaking of exploration, there's really no collectables to speak of, and the only reason to explore would be to find hidden weapons, unlock area shortcuts (very important), and collect other game related items that I never used. Regarding game length, it took me 88 hours to get through my first playthrough. Granted, I died a ton and therefore I had to start from the beginning of the level, over and over.

Look, this was a very difficult game for me to evaluate. While I liked it, I did not love it. Sure, I'm big enough to look past not being able to pause the game, lack of a map, cheap deaths, difficult learning curve, etc. However, I refuse to overlook being forced to start from the beginning of the level, when you die. For the people saying this is an old school type game; this formula can work well with less intense side-scrolling platformers, but NOT an action RPG! That makes the game more frustrating than hard. When a boss kills me, the first thing I want to do is give it another shot. With Bloodborne, (assuming you unlocked the short-cut) you'll have to wait on slow elevators, climb up ladders, and weave through several enemies, just to make it back to the boss and get your rematch. That's unnecessary and beyond ridiculous. Because of this (in addition to the other things I mentioned earlier in the paragraph), I was never really able to fall in love with Bloodborne. So close, but yet so far... Rocket League; you're up next!are no missions or sidemissions in Bloodborne, for the most part. column6: Hyrule Warriors
column13: Pretty fun game with technical issues.
column14:
I'm not the biggest Zelda fan but I did enjoy this game, lots of enemies to fight and a decent amount of missions to do that through. It lacks a bit in the variety of enemies, especially bosses (I think there's 3 minus the characters that double as playable characters). They have it varied up well enough either way in missions that keeps things interesting, there's plenty of characters to use and they all have their own amusing moves. The art design with the characters is also well done, I like that they changed Link up and his origins, Impa looks awesome and is even more fun to play, etc etc, full marks.

The bad side is this game ...pushes the WiiU beyond it's limits. While it does have a lot going on it also suffers with pop-in, especially when playing co-op where it's REALLY bad. I've run up to areas where the map says there's tons of enemies only for them to slowly spawn in right next to me in small groups. That said the game when played in co-op also lowers the resolution and graphical fidelity in an attempt to keep all this fun action going but the framerate dips pretty hard at times and as stated the pop-in is really, really bad.

That is by no means a killer for this game, it's just something that is worth noting. I think they would have been better off pulling the graphics back a bit, if only to make it run better and have less issue with the enemies popping in. The only other complaint is, it can be grindy if you're doing the adventure mode (I think that's what the mode is called), it's fun but they really have an odd way about letting you do quests...

DLC NOTE: I'm not knocking the game itself for this, this is strictly about the DLC and does not hamper the game/review in anyway. There's DLC for this game, a lot of it, most of it's characters or skins and honestly the prices they're asking for are far too much. DLC can make a game more fun but when the price encroaches the cost of the game itself and it's not the same amount of content in the game, I get off put personally.
I'm sure it's well crafted but 20 bucks for some characters ...is not what I think is a great deal when the game offers far more for a better cost. There's some packs to save you money but honestly I cannot justify spending the money they're asking.
----

Either way, it's a solid game on the WiiU that suffers from technical issues.

column6: Killzone: Shadow Fall (PlayStation 4)
column14: Too little people playing I felt, I miss being able to pick and choose your servers. column6: Hyperdimension Neptunia U: Action Unleashed - PlayStation Vita
column13: New to the series with Rebirth 1 & 2 on PC, now this.
column14: Alright I'll start by saying I'm new to the series with Rebirth 1 & 2 being games I found fun on PC, this game ...mixed bag for me personally.  I have no problem with hack and slash games, they can be some good fun but the problem is this game offers no variety in it's enemies, nor any form of challenge. I'm not asking for a game to be crushing, I'm asking this game to offer something other than punching bags that will rarely consider attacking. Unless you're under-leveled I don't think it's possible to lose a match in this, some will note a 1-3 hits can knock you out, I find it difficult to see enemies even attempt to strike.  The action itself is flashy and interesting to look at, each character has a neat variety of moves and skills you can throw in to change up the pace. You're expected to bring in 2 characters to each mission, this allows you to build a special gauge up faster and raise survivability- as well as raise your "lily rank" which helps characters fight together better.  The levels are very small for the most part, basically arenas that just cram in the enemies that spawn in in waves till you clear it. The only variety you'll find in the quests are the 'irregular quests' which are dumb, incredibly dumb. They do not tell you the objective, they just want you to either figure it out or exit the quest where they'll talk about it and give a very vague hint or two at what to do and that's it. These missions are also important since they give good equipment- the REAL kicker is if you do a quest that progresses the story you may entirely lose access to these missions even if you do a New Game+.  Here's my biggest gripe, I'm sure fans are okay with it but I just found it stupid. The fanservice, the clothes in this game get destroyed as you take hits, when it finally does you're 'treated' to a cutscene where you see the clothes get tattered. This would be worth a chuckle, I guess if half of them looked over 15 (yes, I know, they're Goddesses that are thousands of years old but they just LOOK like kids) two of them look like they're 8 or something and I personally have no interest in that kind of fanservice in general and have even less in seeing it happen to the younger ones. There an optional equipment bit to stop this from happening but you have to earn it with EVERY character and they punish you for using it since clothing-break is a game mechanic that when it happens it buffs your special gauge. It didn't stop me from equipping unbreakable clothes on everyone and still breezing through the game. ^ I don't care if fanservice is a theme of the series, I don't care that the dev made a similar game like this. It's something I'm not a fan of. I didn't know what to expect going in and while I'm not offended by this nor am I asking for censorship- I just didn't like the aspect of it. I'm anti-censorship so, don't assume I'm asking for anything.  The other issue is the game's assets are reused from the previous 2 games on the vita, the stages, character avatars, & enemies are ripped right out of the games entirely with no effort. As are many of the songs, maybe all of them.  It's flashy, it's mind-numbingly easy, I personally didn't care for the fan service. The game is mediocre, with the incredible amount of reused content & braindead AI the game feels weak. It isn't BAD, it's serviceable and I'm sure fans of the series will get a kick out of it.  The characters are amusing as they ever were (though it lacks IF, so I'm sad) but the story sadly doesn't carry the game well, the series always had a simple plot which is fine but this one is ...lacking. Either way I'm rambling again.   I would honestly look up a youtube video or two to get an idea of the game. I thought the game would get more challenging but it didn't, just very repetitive even for a hack and slash game like this, while mildly entertaining I don't know if even die-hard fans would get a kick out of it. It's not awful, there's nothing technically wrong with it gameplay wise, it's just very ...lazy I guess is the word for it.

column6: The Evil Within
column13: I died 169 times and it was totally worth it.
column14:
This was genuinely a fun game that sits solidly within the survival horror genre so if you‚Äôre not prepared to die hundreds of times you might want to avoid this. (I died 169 times during my first play through) If you‚Äôre a fan of Shinji Mikami other games like Resident Evil and Resident Evil 4 there is a lot here that will feel familiar without feeling clichéd. The story is a bit convoluted and because I had to play it over several months I lost the plot line and had to double check online to remind myself what was happening. The boss fights can be intense, but you‚Äôre never really without the supplies needed to defeat them. This fact can be both a good quality and a bit underwhelming as by the end you begin to feel increasingly like victory is certain and the game‚Äôs overall difficulty seems to diminish. All that being said, The Evil Within is actually very tense with some nice scares, a short learning curve, some very bizarre scenery, and a nice balance between difficulty and playability.

PS. The Keeper was a thoroughly original monster. You‚Äôll see what I mean.

column6: Nintendo Wii U Console - 32GB Black Deluxe Set
column14: This might not be the most powerful system in this generation, or the most successful one at that, but for what it is, it's actually a fun system to play with.  With games like Super Smash Bros., Splatoon, and Bayonetta 2, along with the whole Wii library, there's a good amount of games on the system.  The biggest part of the system is the controller itself, which is actually pretty light in weight and pretty comfortable to hold.  The screen on the controller is also not that bad, though most of the time, it's used as either an extension of the HUD (I guess you can say) or a second screen for if someone wants to watch a show on TV.  You want to be careful with this controller, though, as you can't just buy another tablet controller off the shelf, and there's probably no telling what a replacement one costs.  The console is also compatible with the original Wii accessories, with those accessories being used in Wii U games also, and games, making it the only console in the market available, at least before Microsoft brings the feature to the Xbox One via an update, to be backwards compatible.  I highly recommend this console for someone who is a fan of Nintendo games, though it is available for at least $200 on Nintendo's online store, which is where I got mine.  It also makes a great secondary console alongside the PS4, Xbox One, or PC.

column6: TNTi™ Arc Charger - Playstation 4 DualShock Controller Charger with AC adapter PS4 Pro and Slim compatible
column13: This is such a smart order to go along with the PS4.
column14:
-Doesn't have trouble holding both controllers at once (no tipping over),
-Indication lights do not diminish but stay a steady vibrant colour (green and red)
-Material is not heavy at just 8 ounces making it easy to handle.
-Solid build causes no concern for accidental breakage from handling too roughly
-and the controllers have no trouble with aligning into the slot.

5 Stars for all the above and the 2 additional USB ports, included cables and AC adapter.

A Note on the USB Ports:
Although you can charge your iPhone from the side USB ports on the charger it will not be able to tell when your phone is completely charged up. The reason for this is because of the technology used in the charger is designed for and compatible only with the Sony batteries in the ps4 controllers and the not the batteries in the apple products. So the charger can tell when the Sony battery is fully charged and turn to green but when another type of battery is being charged it can not tell so it may remain red.

Personally:
I had such a problem with leaving my $60 "Sony DualShock 4 Wireless Controller for PlayStation 4" anywhere, losing it quickly, requiring me to purchase another controller (in a different colour so I'd know which one was lost) for back up to have charged and potentially not misplaced. That didn't help my disorganized habit. I had the opportunity to request this for evaluation and review and I'm so happy that it was provided to me by TNT Interactive because now the controllers are always in the cradle if not in use. It wasnt a hard habit to break because the ease of knowing where my controller was and knowing that it was charged made my PS4 experience a lot smoother when dealing with Netflix asking if I'm still watching something, So much so that I wish I had two. One for my bedside and one next to my console.

column13: It's rolling the dice on build quality.
column14: [UPDATE] I ended up turning my warranty repair into my credit card company.  They paid for the repair.  I would never purchase another console without an extended warranty on top of paying with a credit card with an additional buyer protection plan. -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------  If it works then it's a good console experience, not great, but good.  The problem is the build quality is really poor. When you contact support they will dismiss your issues or tell you they will push a software update to fix it. But when they don't they will continue to deny the issue or keep promising future software fixes. Then after your hardware warranty expires they immediately give you the "option" to send it in for repair at a cost of about $125. But if you go online to process you'll save $10.  It's very clear MS has no intentions on honoring their warranty or dealing with legitimate returns.  When you are able to play games it's a good console. Interface is improving and game selection is the best imo.  It's just a roll of the dice if you're getting good hardware or not. If you don't...it's a nightmare.

column13: Nice headset, faint issues with audio.
column14:
[[VIDEOID:9426bb6c9792eb00b2e2c4e77b8ad07b]] Hello Amazon!

Just want it to be noted that I received a free sample for this review, and it has not affected the review, and the video is actually just a microphone test with some stock photography over it.

STEP 1. AUDIO QUALITY
The audio quality sounds great on this headset. I could real feel a thud when the bass struck, and the highs and lows sounds great too. The volume can go high enough to almost hurt your ears, and at max when you take the headset off, you can hear it from up to 5 feet away. I'm no audiophile, but I have listened to and owned some high quality headphones, and the sound ranks right up there near them. (Test Music - Turn Down For What - DJ Snake)

STEP 2. BUILD QUALITY
Right out of the box, these headphones look great. The build is a shiny plastic, with leather pads on the headband and ears. The padding on the ears is big enough to go all the way over my ears, so I can wear them for a long time, but not too big to be uncomfortable. The USB is the only thing off about this, as it is only used for the LED on the sides of the ears. The LED is not too bright, and is mainly used for the effect.This headset is big, no doubt about it. My estimate for fitting age is possible 12 - adult, so they are great for everyone.

STEP 3. MICROPHONE QUALITY
The microphone quality review is listed in the video, so the only thing I want to point out here is that there is a faint buzzing / feedback in the audio. Other than that, it is good.

Thank you for listening, and reading my review! If this was helpful to you, hit that little thumbs up button below.

column6: HDE Clear Case Cover for Nintendo 3DS
column14:
This is a great case for your 3DS and at a bargain too. The case snapped nicely into place and keeps my 3DS from getting scratched or covered with fingerprints. The case is made of clear plastic and is thin enough where it won't add too much bulk to the 3DS itself, but can still protect it from minor bumps and drops. The cutouts on the case are well made and don't interfere with any of the ports or cameras. It is slightly difficult to attach and remove the back half of the case, but I have no problem with this, since it means it won't be coming off accidentally. This case does a great job of keeping my 3DS nice and clean and I would recommend it to anyone looking for a case to showcase their 3DS without breaking the bank. Its true that this case probably wouldn't stand up to being tossed around, but if you plan to handle your game that way, you might as well get a nerf case.

Bottom line is that this is a great case at an unbeatable price and will keep your 3DS protected under regular use.

column6: Motionsports: Adrenaline - Playstation 3
column13: The two handed older dude's blues
column14: The idea of this game is actually very good :) For an adult player it can get a bit irritating to crash into the cliffs, gliding like a nylon squirrel, and then effortlessly return to the main falling pathway. But the biggest flaw is inability to use TWO Move sticks :( Honestly, I felt so out of balance and whatever, that I just held both sticks while cycling or rowing, even if the second one did not actually interact with the Move's Eye. If you guys are going to make Motionsports 2, PLEASE at least include an option to use not just one, but two sticks. You know, for us - the ignorant majority with two hands...
